EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In late October, a winter storm dumped heavy snow in eastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota over a period of 2 days. Due to mesoscale forces at play, some areas received a foot of snow or more where the band stalled. In addition to heavy snow, there was also blowing snow, reducing visibility across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reports 7.5 inches at Black Tiger Bay Campground in Saint Michael.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of of resistant aufeis in the main channel of the Sagavanirktok (Sag) River during spring breakup forced the Sag River flow toward Milepost 403 of the Dalton Highway. The high flow from snowmelt and a heavy rain on snow event in the Brooks Range on June 10th exacerbated the impacts to the Dalton Highway.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The main flow of the Sagavanirktok (Sag) River was diverted to the farthest west channel of the river due to aurfeis blocking the channel. The Sag River was pushed up against the Dalton Highway and began to erode the road near Milepost 403.5. On June 7th the road was closed at Milepost 403.5 due to the Sag River eroding the highway to the centerline with the threat of a total washout. This closure shut off the only road access to the oil fields on the North Slope of Alaska. The AK Department of Transportation immediately began hauling rock from a quarry 150 miles away in order to secure the road. The road reopened to one lane traffic on June 8th, although the threat of erosion continued for another week. Runoff from heavy rain and snowmelt in the headwaters of the Sag River reached Milepost 403.5 of the Dalton Highway on June 14th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous short-wave trough interacted with an approaching low pressure system and associated warm frontal boundary to trigger clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms across west-central Illinois during the late afternoon of August 6th.  Due to enhanced low-level wind shear along and north of the warm front, many of the cells began rotating and spinning up occasional funnel clouds.  One of the cells intensified as it pushed into Sangamon County, producing a long-track tornado that was on the ground for over 25 miles from just north of Pawnee in far southeastern Sangamon County to southeast of Stonington in Christian County.  The tornado produced EF-1 damage along much of its path, peaking with EF-2 damage just south of Willeys in Christian County.  This particular thunderstorm cell dropped 2-inch diameter hail north of Taylorville and went on to produce a downburst with 80 mph wind gusts in far eastern Shelby County near Lake Mattoon.  The storms eventually congealed into a line as they pushed into eastern Illinois later in the evening, with scattered wind damage, hail, and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter estimated a 60 mph wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combined effects of persistent above-normal temperatures and minimal precipitation starting in early July 2023 resulted in mounting drought impacts across much of the state of Mississippi. Through the month of October, D2 (Severe Drought) and D3 (Extreme Drought) conditions, as depicted on the U.S. Drought Monitor, expanded from southern and central areas to also affect northern Mississippi. D4 (Exceptional Drought) conditions expanded farther across central and southwestern portions of the state including most areas encompassed by a loop from Vicksburg to Kosciusko to Philadelphia to Columbia. Average temperatures for the month especially in the most impacted areas ranged from 2 to 4 degrees F above normal, and several daily temperature records were set. Observed precipitation values across a vast majority of the state were less than 25 percent of normal. In southeastern Mississippi where around 2 to 3 inches of rain fell during the month - about 70 percent of normal - average temperatures were about 1 degree below normal. Soil moisture values continued to worsen through the month, with subsoil moisture values between 25 to 50 percent below normal for much of the affected area. This placed a severe stress on pastures for livestock and reduced the yield from row crops to end the growing season. Pine plantations and Christmas tree farms experienced severe losses especially among younger trees. Streamflows on creeks and rivers were reduced.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Drought conditions in Montgomery County intensified from D2 (Severe Drought) to D4 (Exceptional Drought) as depicted on the U.S. Drought Monitor.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread severe weather was observed across Eastern Nebraska on the afternoon and evening of July 4. Storms initially were discrete or multi-clustered and produced mainly hail. The largest hail report was 2.75 inches near Tarnov in Platte County. A QLCS formed as storms merged along a cold front and strong wind gusts became the primary hazard. Numerous locations observed 60+ mph wind gusts. An estimated peak wind gust of 80 mph caused damage to trees and power poles near Weston.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported a large tree snapped off via social media.

A stalled frontal boundary remained over the area which produced multiple rounds of torrential rainfall form heavy thunderstorms from July 9th through July 10th. CAPE values of 2500 to 3500 J/kg and PWAT values of near 1.8 allowed heavy thunderstorm development to produce rainfall rates of 2-3 inches per hour at times. There were parts of the area that receive anywhere from 3-5 inches of rain in a several hour period with some spots seeing upwards of 8 inches. This allowed for the issuance of a localized Flash Flood Emergency for portion of the Lower Hudson Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Video of water rushing down Wixon Pond Road and East Lake Blvd in Carmel, NY.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along an old outflow boundary across parts of central and east central Missouri. Some of the storms produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread wind damage across Farmington. Numerous trees, tree limbs and power lines were blown down. Also, a couple of power poles were knocked down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported a peak measured wind gust of 74 mph.

The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported a medium sized tree snapped at the trunk.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front produced heavy snow for the Oregon Cascades. Cold Air in the Columbia Gorge resulted in heavy snow as a front associated with an atmospheric river produced precipitation across NW Oregon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained Skywarn Spotters reported 4 to 6.5 inches of snow in Hood River at elevations 200 feet and below near Highway 84 in the morning of December 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong front produced hevy snow for the Southwest Washington Cascades. Cold Air in the Columbia Gorge resulted in heavy snow as a front associated with an atmospheric river produced precipitation across Southwest Washington. Washington Department of Transportation closed Highway 14 through the Columbia River Gorge between mileposts 18 and 43 due to the snow causing multiple vehicle spinouts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained Spotters reported 5 to 8 inches of snow around Skamania near Highway 14 the morning of December 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front associated with an occluding surface low over the upper Midwest pushed through the waters in the early morning hours of January 4th. Along the front, a line of thunderstorms formed and pushed through the waters, bringing winds of over 34 knots. The cold front, and subsequent thunderstorms, exited the outer waters by 12Z.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station XMVL recorded a thunderstorm wind gust of 43 mph or 37 knots.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A pair of moderate atmospheric rivers brought heavy rain leading to minor river and urban flooding to portions of northwest Oregon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Siuslaw river at Mapleton rose above minor flood stage after noon on December 3rd and crested at 18.7 feet at 6 PM. Flood stage is 18.0 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winds impacts for metro and columbia river gorge including power outages.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet stations measured gusts of 45 to 50 mph. Multiple reports of fallen trees on power lines. Hundreds of PGE customers without power in Clackamas, Washington and Multnomah Counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong front produced a burst of high winds along the North Oregon Coast on December 4, 2023.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several wind measuring sites measured high winds along the Oregon coast December 4th through December 5th. The peak measured wind was 71 mph at Garibaldi.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong atmospheric river brought heavy rains on December 5th which led to minor river and urban flooding across portions of southwest Washington. Clark County and Cowlitz County saw landslides, along with minor river flooding, including the Cowlitz River at Kelso and the Grays River near Rosburg. Portions of the Willapa Hills and south Washington Cascades received 12 to 16 inches of rain over a 5 day period beginning December 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The AMTRAK rail experienced a small landslide on their track between mile marker 129 and 130.5 near Felida and canceled the train between Seattle and Portland through December 7th. No impacts other than their internal transportation delays occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level trough ejected over the Southern Plains which caused rapid surface cyclogenesis to occur in southeast Texas. This surface low traversed across central and northern Louisiana. The rapid development of the surface low gave way to very high shear values, and with enough instability, a line of thunderstorms formed along its cold front. A couple of brief tornadoes occurred with the line in Pointe Coupee and Terrebonne Parishes. The Pointe Coupee Parish tornado resulted in 3 injuries. Otherwise, damaging wind gusts were noted with the line due to the extreme shear. The line exited southeast Louisiana in the early morning hours of the 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency manager reported a travel trailer rolled and was destroyed on Stewart Street. Time estimated from radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong atmospheric river brought heavy rains on December 5th which led to minor river and urban flooding across portions of southwest Washington. Clark County and Cowlitz County saw landslides, along with minor river flooding, including the Cowlitz River at Kelso and the Grays River near Rosburg. Portions of the Willapa Hills and south Washington Cascades received 12 to 16 inches of rain over a 5 day period beginning December 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Grays River rose above flood stage on December 4th, cresting at 16.24 feet on December 5th at 9 am, and fell below flood stage on December 6th. Flood stage is 12.0 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dense Fog in the Central Willamette Valley contributed to a aircraft accident. A small plane struck power pole and power lines near Independence, Oregon and crashed just outside airport grounds, killing all three people onboard.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense Fog in the Central Willamette Valley contributed to deadly aircraft accident.  A single engine airplane travelling from McMinnville to Independence crashed around 4:55 PM into a power pole just outside of the Independence Airport. The crash resulted in a local power outage, a small brushfire and the loss of all three people on board the airplane.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A southwesterly swell of 20 to 25 ft with a period of 17 seconds was observed across the coastal waters, resulting in a high threat of sneaker waves.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A southwesterly swell of 20 to 25 ft with a period of 17 seconds was observed across the coastal waters. A 5 year old girl was hospitalized after she was hit by a sneaker wave near South Jetty Beach in Florence, OR.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front sagged south into the region on June 12th. The combination of frontal lift, ample moisture, strong daytime heating, and dry air aloft provided the prime setup for severe winds across southwest Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local Sheriffs office reported trees downed by thunderstorm winds in Poplarville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front sagged south into the region on June 12th. The combination of frontal lift, ample moisture, strong daytime heating, and dry air aloft provided the prime setup for severe winds across southwest Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local emergency manager reported a tree downed onto a home by thunderstorm winds on Hyde Street near North Jackson Street in Poplarville. Trees were uprooted and powerlines downed in the nearby area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moderate winter storm impacted Southwestern California early in the month. Rainfall totals ranged from 0.50 to 1.50 inches across coastal and valley areas with 1 to 3 inches across the mountains. Cold air, associated with the storm, dropped snow levels to around 3000 feet. So, there were significant snowfall accumulations in the local mountains. Scattered thunderstorms also developed, producing some wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong and gusty northerly winds impacted the eastern range of the Santa Ynez Mountains. Some peak gusts from the local mesonet include: Montecito Hills (gust 71 MPH) and La Granada Mountain (gust 66 MPH).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Enhanced Risk was issued for severe weather on May 7. A shortwave moving across the area interacted with a couple of surface boundaries in the area initiating severe weather. There was video of a weak tornado that didn't produce any damage. There were several hail reports the largest of which was 2.25 inches in Mills County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported 1-inch hail.

CZ_NAME: SAN LUIS OBISPO COUNTY INTERIOR VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another strong winter storm impacted Southwestern California. The storm brought winter storm conditions the local mountains with snowfall totals of 2 to 4 feet and southerly winds gusting in excess of 80 MPH. Other areas also experienced some strong winds. Additionally, scattered thunderstorms developed across the area, spawning two weak tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong southerly winds impacted the interior valleys of San Luis Obispo county. Some peak wind gusts from the local mesonet include: Navajo Flats (gust 59 MPH) and Lewis Ranch Road (gust 58 MPH).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: One last Winter storm impacted Southwestern California in the month of March. Rainfall totals across the area ranged between 1 and 3 inches which produced numerous reports of nuisance urban flooding. In the mountains of Los Angeles county, snowfall totals up to 12 inches, combined with wind gusting to 67 MPH, generated winter storm conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winter storm conditions developed across the eastern range of the San Gabriel Mountains. Above 5000 feet, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were reported. Additionally, southerly winds, gusting up to 67 MPH, were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low-pressure system which had been moving slowly off the lee side of the Rocky Mountains had finally progressed into central Nebraska. This left western Iowa in the warm sector as a warm front moved north into the area. The SPC issued an Enhanced Risk for severe weather with a 30% hatched for severe hail. The severe weather mostly stayed west of the Missouri River. In Iowa, there was one report for a severe wind gust. The most impactful weather was a line of training storms that lead to flash flooding in Harrison County that caused significant damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported 4.4 inches of rainfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low crossed the region during the 5th. Instability due to diurnal heating and the cold pool aloft supported the development of thunderstorms during the afternoon. Isolated strong to severe thunderstorms occurred across portions of Downeast Maine with hail and damaging winds.

High pressure at the surface and aloft brought hot temperatures and high dew points to the region during the 6th. Afternoon temperatures ranged from the mid 80s to around 90...with dew points from the upper 60s to lower 70s...across much of northern and eastern Maine. Heat Index values generally ranged from the mid 90s to around 100 degrees...locally up to 105.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High temperatures ranged from the mid 80s to around 90...with dew points from the upper 60s to lower 70s. This combination produced Heat Index values generally ranging from the mid 90s to around 100 degrees...locally up to around 105.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Enhanced Risk was issued for severe weather on May 7. A shortwave moving across the area interacted with a couple of surface boundaries in the area initiating severe weather. There were numerous hail and wind reports across the area. The largest hail report was 2.5 inches in Lancaster County and the highest measured wind gust was 73 mph in Richardson County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public sent a video and a detailed report of what appeared to be a gustnado that tracked south to north for approximately 1 mile. The winds were strong enough to snap a few 8-inch diameter tree branches. This feature occurred on the north edge of a developing storm with winds gusting from south to north in the area just east of the dust whirl.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On May 16, 2023, a 1002 mb low moving through the Bering Sea brought blizzard conditions to the Bering Strait.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Blizzard conditions developed on the Bering Strait coast early in the morning, of the 16th and continued into the early evening. Blizzard conditions were reported at both Brevig Mission and Wales. Brevig Mission had two distinct periods of blizzard conditions during this event, with blizzard conditions present for much of the morning, with a second shorter period in the evening. Wales reported blizzard conditions for much of the morning of the 16th. Brevig Mission reported a peak wind gust of 48 mph during the event, while the peak wind gust at Wales was 41 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered late afternoon storms produced damaging winds across southeast Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered late afternoon storms produced damaging winds across southeast Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees and powerlines were blown down in town. Several trees were down across roads as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather front brought from 1 to 2 inches of rain to the headwaters of Birch Creek and Crooked Creek. The rain fell on a residual winter snowpack and resulted in significant runoff due to the combination of rapid snowmelt and the heavy rainfall. This caused high water and flooding along rivers and streams draining the region including Crooked Creek and Birch Creek which impacted the community of Central and portions of the Steese Highway. Flooding started in late May and continued into early June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain and snowmelt in the Birch Creek headwaters caused Birch Creek to flow overbank and flood portions of the Steese Highway between milepost 145 to 147. The flooding caused the highway to be closed for a period of time due to dangerous driving conditions. Birch Creek fell back within bank on June 2nd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak upper-level wave moving through southwest flow aloft, acting on an environment with 1000 to 1500 J/kg of MUCAPE in the vicinity of a surface trough, resulted in scattered thunderstorms across far southeast South Dakota, far northeast Nebraska, northwest Iowa, and southwest Minnesota during the evening of April 19th. The strongest storms produced severe hail ranging from 1.0 to 1.5 inches in diameter.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail 1.0 inch in diameter fell 5 miles west-northwest of Sioux City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Most of the region was in Extreme (D3) to Exceptional (D4) Drought for entire month of September.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The county was in Extreme (D3) to Exceptional (D4) Drought for entire month of September due a long duration lack of rainfall and a very hot, dry period.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down onto a powerline along Woody Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of storms moved up from the southwest during the afternoon and produced wind damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another unseasonably strong upper trough approached the region during the day on the 17th. Widespread thunderstorm development occurred across the High Plains, from southwest Kansas into the central Texas Panhandle by the late afternoon. The combination of anomalously (for mid-June) high magnitudes of wind shear and instability produced widespread severe weather outcomes across southern, central and northern Oklahoma. By the late evening hours, convection had organized into a mature bow echo across north-central Oklahoma, where numerous significant wind gusts (and damage) were observed. Similar outcomes occurred into portions of northeastern Oklahoma towards early morning hours of the 18th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado developed and produced a Tornadic Debris Signature (TDS) on the KVNX radar north of Burlington. The tornado moved primarily over cropland, although it did apparently damage a few trees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Drier air began to work into eastern Utah in the wake of a recent monsoon surge. Even so, enough residual moisture was present to fuel isolated thunderstorms. Some storms produced wind gusts in excess of 58 mph in Grand County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 60 MPH was measured by the automated weather station at the Canyonlands Field Airport outside of Moab.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary just north of southwest New Hampshire allowed for this region of the state to stay in a moist and unstable airmass on the afternoon of June 26th.  Thunderstorms begin to develop during the afternoon hours and continued into the evening.  Most storms remained on the week, except for one isolated storm along the Connecticut River Valley in Cheshire County which became severe.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorm outflow winds downed multiple trees onto buildings in the Spofford Lake area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front draped over the region provided the focus for slow moving thunderstorm activity over northeastern Pennsylvania. Localized areas of 2 to 4 inches of rainfall contributed to some small stream and creek flooding near the Delaware River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported water, rocks and gravel running across Twin Lakes Road near the Handsome Eddy Road intersection due to culvert being blown out by flood waters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm system, with highly anomalous magnitudes of wind shear and moisture for late February, impacted the forecast area on the evening of the 26th. A broken line of severe thunderstorms developed across the eastern Texas Panhandle/far western Oklahoma and quickly swept through much of the forecast area. Widespread wind damage, including gusts near 90 mph, along with a record number of tornadoes (13) for February occurred. Several reports of large hail were also received. Behind the line of thunderstorms, a tight pressure gradient and strong westerly low-level jet allowed widespread 50-60 mph winds gusts to continue through the late evening hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Time is estimated via radar.

An area of freezing fog and low clouds moved south from Saskatchewan into northeastern Montana and remained over the area for a couple days.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At the Beach, ND airport ASOS site (K20U), visibility of a quarter mile or less was recorded for about 26 1/2 hours from early morning on the 11th to the morning of the 12th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of freezing fog and low clouds moved south from Saskatchewan into northeastern Montana and remained over the area for a couple days.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple episodes of intermittent dense fog with visibility of a quarter mile or less occurred at the Circle Town County Airport AWOS (K4U6). The first episode lasted for 3 hours on the morning of the 11th. The second episode lasted 12 1/4 hours from the late afternoon of the 11th to the early morning on the 12th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front moved north into southern New England late on the 22nd and early on the 23rd.  There was elevated instability and a considerable amount of effective shear (around 40 kt) in the elevated-convective level, due to strong mid-upper level SSW flow. One cluster of thunderstorms produced quarter-size hail when it came onshore in Westerly, RI.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A member of the public reported on social media that hail up to quarter size occurred in Westerly, along with frequent lightning.  Report was relayed by amateur radio.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A high pressure system over the central Atlantic was driven moderate to fresh winds, resulting choppy seas impacting the local waters of Puerto Rico. The risk of rip currents was high during this period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Emergency managers, as well as local newspaper, reported the drowning of a 50-year-old male in La Concha Beach in Condado.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms developed during the mid to late afternoon hours. A few produced gusty outflow winds, and even a few isolated microbursts, which knocked down trees in a few areas. Hardest hit areas were in Sheffield and Tuscumbia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down at 917 Pine Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking northeastward across Iowa pushed a cold front into central Illinois during the afternoon of January 3rd.  The arimass ahead of the front became moderately unstable thanks to surface temperatures climbing into the lower to middle 60s and dewpoints hovering near 60 degrees.  Given the instability and increasing amounts of deep-layer wind shear in association with a strong upper low approaching from the west, scattered supercell thunderstorms developed along the front during the afternoon.  The storms were primarily focused in a corridor from Springfield and Taylorville northeastward to near Champaign.  A total of 8 short-lived weak tornadoes touched down within this corridor, with the strongest tornadoes producing EF-1 damage near Maroa and in the Decatur area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado briefly touched down 3 miles southwest of Maroa along Bearsdale Road just north of School Road at 4:33 PM CST.  A power pole and irrigation unit were damaged.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front moved north into southern New England, producing showers and scattered strong thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Westport, police reported a tree down on Briggs Road, caused by a lightning strike.  Report relayed by amateur radio.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple bands of heavy snow. ||A powerful winter storm produced multiple bands of widespread significant snowfall to parts of Western Wisconsin. A Winter Storm Watch was issued on February 19th for the entire County Warning Area to bring attention to the significant system coming a few days later. On February 21st, all counties in Western Wisconsin were upgraded to a Winter Storm Warning for wind gusts of 35-40 mph, and heavy accumulating snow of up to 12-18 inches in some areas. Using the Winter Storm Severity Index, considerable disruptions to daily life were expected. This included avoidance of travel recommendations, and potentially widespread closures to roads and other infrastructure.||Snow began to fall on the afternoon of February 21st and persisted in waves through the afternoon of February 23rd. Wind gust observations did detail some gusts reached  the low to mid 30 mph range. The first band of snow was less significant as compared to the next bands of snow. Overall snow accumulations provided by a combination of trained spotters and the CoCoRaHS observers, verified the forecast. Snowfall accumulations ranged from 8-16 inches across the region. ||Some of the highest snowfall totals included:||15.5 inches 13 miles south of Eau Claire WI.|15 inches near Hudson WI.|15.9 inches 9 miles northeast of New Richmond, WI.|14.7 inches near Chippewa Falls WI.|14.0 inches near Chetek WI.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple bands of snow moved across the county. Sustained winds increased out of the northeast to 20 mph with gusts near 30 mph. Across the county, Interpolated Snowfall Analysis using the National Gridded Snowfall Analysis (NGSA) map detailed that at least 4-6 inches fell in 24 hrs, additional 6-12 inches in 48 hrs and overall snow totals ranging from 8-18 inches. Per CoCoRaHS reports, there was uniform distribution of recorded snowfall ranging from 10-13 inches across the County. The highest snowfall observation was 13.4 inches located just southeast of Menomonie, WI.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A prolonged period of precipitation fell across the county, beginning during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingering into the very early morning of January 30th. There was an estimated light glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered and slick with several schools also closed on January 30th.

During the afternoon of July 13th, a cluster of thunderstorms developed in East-Central Colorado and moved south-southeastward across the region. One of these thunderstorms became severe and produced hail up to baseballs in size within the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Report received of hail up to pennies in size at location.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the morning of July 14th, a cold front passed through Northwestern Kansas allowing for thunderstorms to move through the region. One of these thunderstorms became severe and produced wind gusts up to 70 mph along with quarter sized hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Report received via social media of marble to quarter sized hail at location. Time is radar estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought status improved slightly for some of the counties in Northwest Kansas toward the end of the month.  Rainfall amounts ranged from two to eight inches, with the highest amounts falling over Gove County.  Normal rainfall for the month is three to four inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall amounts for the month ranged from three to eight inches.  This was near normal to five inches above the normal amount of three to four inches of rainfall for the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving upper level disturbance passing southward along the Rocky Mountains brought a potent cold front that surged south through eastern NM. High winds and light to moderate snow accompanied this storm system. High wind gusts greater than 60 mph were observed at Raton and through portions of Union County. The combination of strong winds and blowing snow also caused several road closures and crashes along U.S. Highway 64 from Raton to Clayton, and along I-40 in the Central Highlands. An isolated snowfall accumulation of 5 inches in DeBaca County were reported as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mesonet station southwest of Clayton measured a peak wind gust of 65 mph, with a few other gusts topping 60 mph during this timeframe.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the early evening of June 14th a line of thunderstorms developed across Massachusetts and quickly bowed out across Cheshire and Western Hillsborough County.  The thunderstorms quickly weakened as they moved further west.  Minor tree damage was reported in isolated areas in the Jaffrey area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorm outflow winds downed a few trees on NH Route 137 and Johansen drive in north Jaffrey.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Excessive heat in early July led to record breaking temperatures and Major HeatRisk. Sacramento tied the record high of 109 degrees for July 1st and 2nd. A record high temperature of 109 was set at Stockton Airport where the previous record was 108 for July 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Daytime highs across the zone were in the upper 90s to 110 degree range.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought status for the month changed little for Red Willow County.  Near to below normal rainfall occurred during the month for the county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall amounts for the month ranged from one to three inches.  This was near normal to two inches below the normal amount of three to four inches of rainfall for the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the evening of July 15th, showers and thunderstorms that developed in the Front Range of the Rocky Mountains moved eastward into Northwestern Kansas. One of these thunderstorms became severe and produced hail up to quarters in size as well as wind gusts up to 60 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotter reported 60 mph thunderstorm wind gusts along with quarter sized hail at location for a four minute duration. Spotter's anemometer was damaged by hail.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved south through Southern Nebraska into Northwest Kansas during the late afternoon during the late afternoon and early evening.  Thunderstorm winds were strong enough to break off a six inch diameter tree limb in Benkelman.  The largest hail reported was near Trenton.

The first of two sequential winter storm systems rolled through northern and central New Mexico on February 13, 2023 and February 14, 2023. Heavy snow was reported across much of the northern mountains of New Mexico, as well as a few isolated spots in and around the Santa Fe and Albuquerque metro areas by the morning of February 14, 2023. Snow accumulations reaching 10 to 11 inches were reported atop the Sangre de Cristo Mountains, while severe winter driving conditions were reported on U.S. Highway 64 in the Tusas Mountains. Strong westerly winds filled in quickly as the main upper level low exited the area during the morning of February 14, 2023. High winds with peak gusts of 60 to 70 mph were reported through the southwest mountains, Sandia and Manzano Mountains, and over a large area of the eastern plains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A public weather station measured a 62 mph wind gust at the top of South Baldy in the Magdalena Mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A pair of upper lows became cut off over southern and eastern Montana  extending south and east into the Dakotas and Wyoming from a  negatively-tilted trough centered off the Pacific Northwest  coastline. This cut-off low spun in place through Thursday the 20th. The result was for significant accumulating snow in eastern portions of North-central Montana, with additional heavy snow across much of the rest of Southwest and Central MT.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snotel equipment at Mount Lockhart and Dupuyer creek both estimated 11 inches of new snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The region was in the ascent side of an approaching trough, which in combination with a developing surface low, resulted in widespread snow and heavy snow across much of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple snotels measured snow reaching winter storm warning criteria, including Lemhi Ridge, Darkhorse Lake, and Slagamelt Lakes. The highest accumulation was at the Darkhorse Lake Snotel, which estimated 9 inches new snow in 24 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported a tree down on a house.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed in advance of a cold front crossing the region during the afternoon of the 7th. Slow moving and training thunderstorms across the higher terrain of Baxter State Park produced heavy rain which led to localized flash flooding. Flash flooding developed along the Nesowadnehunk Stream. The Park Tote Road was covered with 8 to 10 inches of running water. The road was closed for several hours until the flash flooding subsided.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding on the Nesowadnehunk Stream flooded the Park Tote Road with 8 to 10 inches of running water. The road was closed for several hours until the flash flooding subsided.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low-pressure system which had been moving slowly off the lee side of the Rocky Mountains had finally progressed into central Nebraska. This left western Iowa in the warm sector as a warm front moved north into the area. The SPC issued an Enhanced Risk for severe weather with a 30% hatched for severe hail. The severe weather mostly stayed west of the Missouri River. In Iowa, there was one report for a severe wind gust. The most impactful weather was a line of training storms that lead to flash flooding in Harrison County that caused significant damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported via mPing of 1-inch tree limbs broken; shingles blown off.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported a semi blown over and part of roof blown off a building.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A pair of upper lows became cut off over southern and eastern Montana  extending south and east into the Dakotas and Wyoming from a  negatively-tilted trough centered off the Pacific Northwest  coastline. This cut-off low spun in place through Thursday the 20th. The result was for significant accumulating snow in eastern portions of North-central Montana, with additional heavy snow across much of the rest of Southwest and Central MT.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snotel station badger Pass estimated 14 inches storm total snow. High snowfall amounts were confined to uninhabited/high elevation areas.

CZ_NAME: GALLATIN AND MADISON COUNTY MOUNTAINS AND CENTENNIAL MOUNTAINS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An impressive shortwave and attendant cold front passed through the area, resulting in a period of gusty winds and intense snow showers. Snow persisted long enough in the mountains to accumulate up to 11 inches in Gallatin County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Red Rock RAWS rrdm8 measured a 65 mph gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough and associated cold front pushed into Western New Hampshire late in the day on July 13th.  A very moist and unstable airmass was firmly in place across the state ahead of the boundary providing sufficient instability.  A line of thunderstorms pushed into the Connecticut River Valley by late evening bringing severe wind gusts and some large hail before the line weakened by the time it reached Central New Hampshire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorm outflow winds downed multiple trees on Jarvis Hill Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On July 16th a widespread area of rain impacted the state.  Rain showers began to develop around daybreak on July 16th and quickly became more widespread during the morning hours.  Light to moderate rainfall became widespread across the state with embedded bands of heavy rain.  Locally heavy rainfall continued straight through the morning hours into early afternoon on the 16th before rainfall intensity and coverage began to decrease.  The heaviest rainfall occurred along the Maine and New Hampshire state line where as much as 5 inches fell over saturated ground. Flood and flash floods were most prevalent across Oxford County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Swift River came out of banks on July 16th following heavy rain showers. The USGS river gage at Roxbury exceeded the flood stage of 7 feet, cresting at 9.2 feet on the 16th. The impacts were flooding of Route 17 in Byron.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving frontal boundary triggers shower and thunderstorms with heavy rainfall on the afternoon of the 7th. The anomalously humid airmass resulted in torrential rainfall rates around 2 to 3 inches per hour and localized flooding across the mountains of western Maine.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported a washout on Goodrich Road near Jackson Brook. Minor washout on Murray Street near McLaughlin Lane. Radar estimated 1 to 3 inches of rain fell across the Bingham Area in the course of an hour and a half.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved approached New Hampshire from the west, bringing a line of showers and thunderstorms. The environment was a continuation of an anomalously moist airmass supportive of torrential rainfall. Ground conditions across New Hampshire were growing saturated, and streams were running high. The storms that developed on the evening of the 13th were concentrated across southwest New Hampshire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain moved into Cheshire County around 8 PM with rainfall rates peaking around 4 inches an hour. In Walpole, Great Brook came out of banks and flooded Old Keene Road near Mill Road and damaged agricultural property off Watkins Hill Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorms with heavy rainfall stalled over the communities of Peru, Jay, and Canton on the evening of the 25th. Radar estimates between 3 to 4.5 inches fell between 6 and 730 pm. The rain fell over saturated ground and hilly terrain. A small tributary called the Tucker Valley Brook came out of banks and washed out a bridge on the Jay-Wilton line.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tucker Valley Brook in Wilton overflowed onto Rollins Ridge Road resulting in a significant washout estimated at 12 yards long and up to 2 lanes wide.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On July 16th a widespread area of rain impacted the state.  Rain showers began to develop around daybreak on July 16th and quickly became more widespread during the morning hours.  Light to moderate rainfall became widespread across the state with embedded bands of heavy rain.  Locally heavy rainfall continued straight through the morning hours into early afternoon on the 16th before rainfall intensity and coverage began to decrease.  The heaviest rainfall occurred along the Maine and New Hampshire state line where as much as 5 inches fell over saturated ground. Flood and flash floods were most prevalent across Oxford County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The main throughfare in Fryeburg, Route 302, flooded in the 300-block area causing significant disruption to travel in and out of the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary and surface low pressure began to slowly lift northward into the southeast New Hampshire through the Midcoast of Maine on the afternoon of the 29th. Showers and thunderstorms developed along the boundary and moved eastward. Since the system as a whole showed very little forward progression, multiple rounds of showers and thunderstorms ended up moving across the same locations multiple times, on top of already saturated soils. This ended up leading to multiple instances of flash flooding, specifically near the coastal counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall with rates between 2 and 4 inches per hour caused a significant washout on Doughty Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first of many rounds of rain moved into the state by daybreak on July 2nd.  Periods of moderate to heavy rain continued through most of the day before ending by evening.  Most areas of the state received 1 to 2 of rain, with the heaviest rain corridor occurring across the Seacoast region of Rockingham and Strafford Counties where 2 to 3 of rainfall occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Suncook River came out of  banks following heavy rain on the 2nd. The water came up to Bachelder Road in Allenstown. Waterfront campsites upstream were inundated. The river crested at 7.5 feet, flood stage is 7.0 feet.

Surface temperatures reaching the mid to upper 90's combined with dew points in the 70s and lower 80s allowed for apparent temperatures, or the heat index, to exceed 105F in rural MN counties and 100F for multiple hours in the Twin Cities metropolitan area. Strong ridging aloft was in place over the southwestern U.S. which allowed for seasonally warm high temperatures to be carried east via zonal flow over the Central U.S. ||In the lower levels, a surface low over the Dakotas along with transport of gulf moisture from the south allowed for dew point temperatures to remain elevated the night prior to July 27th, despite cloud cover lingering from prior convection over the northern plains. As clouds cleared the next day, daytime heating increased surface temperatures in an already humid air mass, causing heat indices to reach dangerous levels. ||Some of the highest heat indices from this event were:|Granite Falls, MN in Yellow Medicine County: 116F |Redwood Falls, MN in Redwood County: 113F|Willmar MN, in Kandiyohi County: 111F|Cambridge, MN in Isanti County: 108F|St. Paul, MN in Ramsey County: 107F|Blaine, MN in Anoka County: 107F|Olivia, MN in Renville County: 107F|Rush City Municipal Airport in Chisago County: 107F|Princeton, MN in Sherburne County: 107F|MSP Intl Airport in Hennepin County: 103F|Airlake Airport in Dakota County: 101F.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Warm environmental temperatures in the upper 90s combined with high dewpoint values in the low to mid 70s, caused high heat indices exceeding 105F for approximately three hours. The ASOS station located at the Cambridge Municipal Airport recorded an apparent temperature of 108F at 2:35 PM (CST).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Prolonged hot and humid conditions coupled with dry mid-levels in the atmosphere, led to extreme amounts of mixed-layer convective available potential energy (MLCAPE). The existence of deep layer shear allowed for numerous strong updrafts to develop across parts of Western WI with the primary hazards being large hail and damaging winds in the afternoon and early evening hours. ||Hail measurements ranged between nickel (0.88 inch) to tea-cup (3.0 inch) size. The largest measured hail was reported 2.5 miles north of Bloomer or 5 miles NW of Chippewa Falls, WI. ||Strong winds uprooted trees, broke large tree branches across, and brought down powerlines across much of the region affected by these storms. The areas with the most wind damage occurred along a line from Polk to Rusk Counties. Strongest wind gusts were estimated to be at least 50 knots or 57 mph.

The areas with the most damage occurred in Chisago County as well as a line from Nicollet to Waseca Counties. The strongest gust (57 mph) was recorded at 11:56 PM at the Mankato Regional Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of storms developed in southern South Dakota and northern Nebraska and moved southeast into Iowa. Initially, storms produced large hail with the largest stones reported at 2.5 inches in Knox County. The storms produced hail across a few counties before eventually transitioning into a wind threat. A 67-mph wind gust was measured at Eppley Airfield but there were no reports of damage across the city of Omaha.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotter reported 1-inch hail.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado impacted a farm on Reflection Lane. There was significant tree damage, windows were blown out of the home, and a large barn had nearly all walls collapse and the roof was removed. There was damage to grain bins farther to the east, and trees were topped to the west along the Nishnabotna River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary remained over the area which produced multiple rounds of torrential rainfall form heavy thunderstorms from July 9th through July 10th. CAPE values of 2500 to 3500 J/kg and PWAT values of near 1.8 allowed heavy thunderstorm development to produce rainfall rates of 2-3 inches per hour at times. There were parts of the area that receive anywhere from 3-5 inches of rain in a several hour period with some spots seeing upwards of 8 inches. This allowed for the issuance of a localized Flash Flood Emergency for portion of the Lower Hudson Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: DOT reports flooding on US 202 both directions at Yorktown. All lanes blocked and local car dealership parking lot flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Multiple bands of accumulating snow. ||A long duration winter storm produced multiple bands of widespread significant snowfall across Minnesota, with persistent northwest winds developing as the storm exited the region. Snow began to fall on the morning of February 21st and persisted in waves through the morning of February 23rd. Wind gust observations were in the low to mid 30 mph range. Overall snow accumulations provided by a combination of trained spotters and the CoCoRaHS observers ranged from 8-16 inches across the region, with a few localized higher amounts. ||Some of the highest snowfall totals across the area include:||16.8 inches near Victoria in Carver County.|16.6 inches near Prior Lake in Scott County.|16.5 inches near Danube in Renville County.|16.5 inches near Faribault in Rice County.|16.1 inches near New Prague in Le Sueur County.|16.0 inches near Prinsburg in Kandiyohi County.|15.9 inches near Cambridge in Isanti County.|15.7 inches near Waseca in Waseca County.|15.4 inches near Stark in Chisago County.|15.3 inches near Corvuso in Meeker County.|15.1 inches near Luxemburg in Stearns County.|15.0 inches near Little Canada in Ramsey County.|15.0 inches near South St Paul in Dakota County.|14.6 inches near New Ulm in Brown County.|14.5 inches near Bethel in Anoka County.|14.2 inches near Edina in Hennepin County.|14.0 inches near Mora in Mille Lacs County.|12.2 inches near Morris in Stevens County.|11.3 inches near Albert Lea in Freeborn County.|11.6 inches near Winnebago in Faribault County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple bands of snow moved across the county. Sustained winds increased out of the northeast near 20-25 mph with gusts near 30-40 mph per the Mankato Airport ASOS observations. Across the county, Interpolated Snowfall Analysis using the National Gridded Snowfall Analysis (NGSA) map detailed that at least 4-8 inches fell in 24 hrs, 4-12 inches in 48 hrs making an overall total range of 8-18 inches. CoCoRaHS and Trained Spotter observations helped verify the NGSA by showing highest snowfall observations located in the northern region of the county with 10-16 measured inches. The highest reported measurement was in 16.1 inches in New Prague, MN.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Even though an old outflow boundary was across southeast Missouri and the far southern portions of Illinois during the morning hours, the boundary dissipated, allowing 75+ dew points to surge north along the Mississippi River. As skies cleared the atmosphere was able to quickly destabilize. Surface based CAPEs were in excess of 3000 J/kg with 40kts of 0 to 6km bulk shear. This combined with a shortwave trough that moved eastward across the region, produced strong to severe storms. There were numerous reports of damaging winds and some reports of large hail. There were three fatalities due to fallen trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down several large trees and numerous tree limbs in the Maryville area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was across portions of southeast Missouri. With plenty of instability, moisture and lift near the boundary, several strong to severe storms developed in this area. There were several reports of damaging winds and large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down several large trees, numerous tree limbs and several power lines around town.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along an old outflow boundary across parts of central and east central Missouri. Some of the storms produced damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down several power lines on Highway Z about 2 miles south of Murry. In Columbia, Numerous trees, tree limbs and power lines were blown down. On tree fell onto a house near the intersection of Ash Street and Greenwood causing moderate roof damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Broad troughing was present aloft across the Western US during the afternoon/evening of the 19th. An area of surface low-pressure slowly deepened and moved towards north-central Kansas, with dryline extending from central Kansas through western-north Texas by the late afternoon hours. A well-timed lead upper wave, combined with broken insolation, led to the development of a few supercell thunderstorms across central Oklahoma. Multiple instances of large to very large (>2 inches) hail, along with 18 tornadoes, occurred across central Oklahoma.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hailfall likely occurred prior to report time (between 1600-1610 CST) based on radar evidence.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure moved northeast from Massachusetts into Maine and New Hampshire on the morning of the 8th. The rainfall intensity increased during peak heating, with the heaviest rainfall from Nashua New Hampshire to Waterville Maine. Rainfall reports were highest across Cumberland and Androscoggin Counties in southern interior Maine ranging between 3 and 5 inches. After a break in the heavy rainfall, another round of scattered heavy rain showers developed in the late evening causing significant flooding in rural northern Franklin County along Rt 17.  Following a very wet July, the water table and streams were all elevated prior to the rains on August 8-9th. The storage for additional rain was limited, which lead to widespread impacts. Flooding was most notable across these locations with numerous flash floods as streams and soil conditions were already swollen.  Several streams came out of banks, as well as the Presumpscot River which reached minor flood stage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Washout on Carver Road near South Monmouth Road likely from the Jock Stream.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The most widespread severe thunderstorm activity in many months broke out across eastern Kentucky on Tuesday, May 16th. A warm front lifted to near the Mountain Parkway during the morning hours, ushering in a muggy airmass for those locations to the south of the Parkway. Sun shining on this juicy air mass helped build up moderate amounts of instability south of the warm front as temperatures warmed into the upper 70s to mid 80s there. Meanwhile, persistent cloud cover and a weak northeasterly breeze north of the front kept temperatures cooler and conditions much more stable. A wave of low pressure rode along the stalled warm front during this afternoon, triggering supercell storms in the area between the warm front and the Hal Rogers Parkway/KY-80 corridor. These storms dropped severe to significant-sized hail. One of the supercells also produced a brief tornado in Magoffin County southwest of Salyersville. Further south, weaker shear led to less organized storm structures, but even there the storms still generated strong outflows leading to bowing storm lines and damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: County dispatch reported power line blown down on Bourne Avenue close to the intersection of Murphy Avenue.

Widespread severe weather was observed across Eastern Nebraska on the afternoon and evening of July 4. Storms initially were discrete or multi-clustered and produced mainly hail. The largest hail report was 2.75 inches near Tarnov in Platte County. A QLCS formed as storms merged along a cold front and strong wind gusts became the primary hazard. These thunderstorms produced numerous large hail, some very large, and severe wind reports. Additionally, flash flooding occurred due to slow-moving high-precipitation supercells.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the evening of the 10th of June a supercell thunderstorm formed northwest of Clayton,  NM. This storm moved southeast through Clayton, where it dropped lots of dime to nickel size hail over the portions of the town. As it got to the southeast of town reports came in of hail up to quarters. This storm continued moving southeast with the main core missing Texline, TX to the south. The storm had weakened a bit, then pulsed up in strength as it followed almost parallel to Highway 87 northwest of Dalhart, TX.  It eventually dropped hail as large as 1.5 (ping pong ball) 8 miles SW of Ware, TX.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface low moved northeastward from central Lower MI to Georgian Bay during the early afternoon through late evening of the 26th. Simultaneously, the attendant warm front moved northeastward from southeastern Lower MI, western and central Lake Erie, and far-eastern OH to the Upper Saint Lawrence River Valley and far-northern NY. Within the warm sector, multiple lines and clusters of multicell thunderstorms persisted generally eastward across northern OH, in vicinity of a surface trough axis, and generated scattered straight-line convective wind damage, a measured severe convective wind gust, and an instance of severe hail. These storms encountered moderate to strong effective bulk shear and primarily moderate to strong MUCAPE.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large tree limb snapped near intersection of Langdon Street and South Avenue in Toledo.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level low off the coast of California helped funnel in subtropical moisture into the state resulting in the development of widespread showers and storms across central and eastern New Mexico June 5th and 6th. Reports of severe weather and flash flooding stretched from the Rio Grande Valley across portions of eastern NM on June 5th. These reports ranged from a landspout tornado near the Petroglyph National Monument and Nara Visa, NM to flash flooding. Another round of severe weather began in the afternoon of June 6th producing more widespread reports over the same area of the state. Reports ranged from burn scar flash flooding within the Hermits Peak/Calf Canyon burn scar and Santa Rosa, to large hail over parts of San Miguel County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public service in Chaves County reported penny size hail on roadway. Roadway was closed for reasons outside of hail accumulation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few severe storms developed over Union County during the late afternoon to early evening hours coinciding with peak heating. The storms moved southeast into the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles following the northwest upper-level flow. There were multiple hail reports ranging in size from pennies to half-dollars. Hail accumulation and heavy rain in Clayton caused some minor flooding impacts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm chaser relayed report of nickel to quarter size hail covering the ground from the first supercell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A passing cold front brought strong storms to northern Illinois during the morning of July 26th. While these storms mostly remained sub-severe, they produced several instances of tree and power line damage. One man was also injured when he was reportedly struck by lightning.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees, tree limbs, and power lines were reported down in Machesney Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: July 28th saw two rounds of severe storms move across the Chicago metro, one during the predawn hours of the morning and another during the evening. The first round brought isolated instances of damaging wind to the area and the second featured damaging winds, severe hail, and 13 tornadoes across the WFO Chicago CWA: 11 in Illinois and 2 in Indiana. Additionally, temperatures in the 90s and high humidity resulted in oppressively hot conditions with afternoon heat indices as high as 105-115F.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local broadcast media relayed to us reports and photos of extensive tree and power line damage in and around Mendota.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A storm survey determined damaging winds accompanied a brief tornado. The damaging winds were offset south and east of the tornado path. At least two dozen trees were downed.

Several consecutive days of significant severe weather impacted eastern New Mexico from May 24-26, 2023. Showers and thunderstorms developed along the dryline and east slopes of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains on May 23rd. Storms tracked east and southeast across the eastern plains of New Mexico. Extensive severe weather was reported when these storms encountered greater moisture and lift closer to the Texas border. Hail up to 3.5 inches in diameter, thunderstorm wind gusts of 80 to 90 mph, and three tornados were reported in an area stretching from Union County to Roosevelt County. The largest hail stones and strongest wind gusts focused throughout Curry County during the evening hours. Hail and wind damage was reported in Tucumcari, Grady, and Clovis. Three separate tornadoes were reported in northern Curry County. Thunderstorms also dropped very heavy rainfall of 2 to 4 inches of rain across portions of Quay, De Baca, Curry, and Roosevelt Counties. Urban flooding occurred in Clovis, NM, causing some roads to be closed, and some cars to be stranded. Severe weather continued through the night and into May 25th with numerous reports of large hail, strong winds, and flash flooding. Quay County was particularly hard hit with baseball size hail and torrential rainfall amounts in excess of 5 inches. Significant hail damage was reported across Tucumcari with widespread flooding across the county. Severe wind gusts of 70 to 80 mph were common with these storms with damage reported. Strong to severe storms continued well into the night once again on the 25th with more heavy rainfall around the Caprock. The focus for severe weather shifted farther west on May 26th with large hail and heavy rainfall reported around Torrance County. A tornado and baseball size hail was also reported with a supercell near Encino. This activity spread eastward through the day with large hail, damaging wind gusts, and more torrential rainfall around the Caprock well into the night of May 26th. Three-day rainfall amounts exceeded 6 inches in many parts of Curry and Quay counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One inch hail was reported just west of San Jon, NM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several consecutive days of significant severe weather impacted eastern New Mexico from May 24-26, 2023. Showers and thunderstorms developed along the dryline and east slopes of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains on May 23rd. Storms tracked east and southeast across the eastern plains of New Mexico. Extensive severe weather was reported when these storms encountered greater moisture and lift closer to the Texas border. Hail up to 3.5 inches in diameter, thunderstorm wind gusts of 80 to 90 mph, and three tornados were reported in an area stretching from Union County to Roosevelt County. The largest hail stones and strongest wind gusts focused throughout Curry County during the evening hours. Hail and wind damage was reported in Tucumcari, Grady, and Clovis. Three separate tornadoes were reported in northern Curry County. Thunderstorms also dropped very heavy rainfall of 2 to 4 inches of rain across portions of Quay, De Baca, Curry, and Roosevelt Counties. Urban flooding occurred in Clovis, NM, causing some roads to be closed, and some cars to be stranded. Severe weather continued through the night and into May 25th with numerous reports of large hail, strong winds, and flash flooding. Quay County was particularly hard hit with baseball size hail and torrential rainfall amounts in excess of 5 inches. Significant hail damage was reported across Tucumcari with widespread flooding across the county. Severe wind gusts of 70 to 80 mph were common with these storms with damage reported. Strong to severe storms continued well into the night once again on the 25th with more heavy rainfall around the Caprock. The focus for severe weather shifted farther west on May 26th with large hail and heavy rainfall reported around Torrance County. A tornado and baseball size hail was also reported with a supercell near Encino. This activity spread eastward through the day with large hail, damaging wind gusts, and more torrential rainfall around the Caprock well into the night of May 26th. Three-day rainfall amounts exceeded 6 inches in many parts of Curry and Quay counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: There was a thunderstorm wind gust estimated to 60 mph just southeast of Cannon Air Force Base. No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong system moved through Eastern Washington and brought scattered thunderstorms. The main areas stretched along Highway 2 from Waterville Plateau to Northern Spokane County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported landspout near Wilbur Airport. No damage reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A backdoor front brought moist easterly upslope flow into northeastern NM on June 11th and June 12th. Discrete supercells fired up along the east slopes of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains during the early afternoon hours of June 11th dropping large to destructive hail as they translated east towards the Texas and Oklahoma Panhandles. More storms developed off the east slopes of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains around sunset dropping more large to destructive hail across the region during the overnight hours into Monday morning. Storms eventually trained over the same areas resulting in major flash flooding over Colfax, Union, Mora and Harding Counties. More discrete supercells fired up midday June 12th tracking east before exiting into the Texas Panhandle around sunset.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ping pong ball sized hail fell with a supercell as it moved southeast through southern Union County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms developed ahead of a frontal boundary and moved across Lake Michigan during the morning hours of July 26, 2023. These thunderstorms would eventually track across the state into a very warm and unstable environment. The southern end of the line of storms is where the strongest winds associated with the line would develop and moved across the lower portions of southeast Michigan during the afternoon between 2 PM and 5 PM. A swath of widespread 60-70 mph wind gusts with locally higher gusts resulted in numerous downed trees, downed powerlines, and around 165,000 power outages in southeast Michigan. The Ann Arbor and the Detroit/Grosse Pointe areas were hit the hardest.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weak tornado with maximum winds of 70 mph tracked east-northeast from northeast Jackson County and briefly crossed into Livingston County before dissipating just northeast of Leeke Road and north of Bowdish Road. One business along the path sustained some minor structural damage that included roof damage and siding damage to an outbuilding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Northern Ohio remained in a very humid air mass and along the northwestern flank of the Bermuda-Azores subtropical surface high pressure ridge during the late morning of the 28th into the 29th before a cold front swept southeastward across the region during the late morning through early afternoon of the 29th. Behind the front, a secondary trough axis moved generally southward across northern OH during the afternoon through early evening before another ridge built from the Canadian Prairies and northern Great Plains during the rest of the 29th. ||Ahead of the cold front, northern OH resided in an environment comprised of moderate to strong effective bulk shear and primarily moderate to strong MUCAPE. Along and ahead of the cold front, multiple rounds of multicell thunderstorms persisted generally eastward across northern OH. These storms produced sporadic straight-line convective wind damage in addition to a mesovortex-related tornado near Bucyrus, OH.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees downed about three-miles west of Butler.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface low moved northeastward from central Lower MI to Georgian Bay during the early afternoon through late evening of the 26th. Simultaneously, the attendant warm front moved northeastward from southeastern Lower MI, western and central Lake Erie, and far-eastern OH to the Upper Saint Lawrence River Valley and far-northern NY. Within the warm sector, multiple lines and clusters of multicell thunderstorms persisted generally eastward across northern OH, in vicinity of a surface trough axis, and generated scattered straight-line convective wind damage, a measured severe convective wind gust, and an instance of severe hail. These storms encountered moderate to strong effective bulk shear and primarily moderate to strong MUCAPE.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fallen tree injured two boys on Nevada Street, between Thurston Street and Dover Place in Toledo.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lake Erie remained along the northwestern flank of the Bermuda-Azores subtropical surface high pressure ridge on the 28th into the 29th before a cold front swept southeastward across the lake during the late morning of the 29th. Behind the front, a secondary trough axis swept generally southward across Lake Erie during the afternoon before another ridge built from the Canadian Prairies and northern Great Plains during the rest of the 29th. ||Ahead of the cold front, Lake Erie resided in an environment comprised of moderate to strong effective bulk shear and primarily moderate to strong MUCAPE. Multiple rounds of multicell thunderstorms persisted generally eastward across Lake Erie during the afternoon of the 28th through early morning of the 29th and generated gale-force peak convective wind gusts along the OH shore. During the afternoon of the 29th, a couple of non-mesocyclonic waterspouts were generated by the updrafts of cumuliform clouds that accompanied the aforementioned secondary surface trough axis and a downshear gust front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Cleveland Water Alliance Maumee Bay Buoy, about four-miles northeast of Oregon, recorded a peak wind gust of 40 mph from a thunderstorm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few severe storms developed over Union County during the late afternoon to early evening hours coinciding with peak heating. The storms moved southeast into the Texas and Oklahoma panhandles following the northwest upper-level flow. There were multiple hail reports ranging in size from pennies to half-dollars. Hail accumulation and heavy rain in Clayton caused some minor flooding impacts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotter Network report of half dollar size hail on the northern outskirts of Clayton from second supercell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Two waves of thunderstorms in central Minnesota produced significant wind damage. A brief EF-0 tornado occurred near Rockford, MN in Wright County during the first wave of storms. The strongest estimated thunderstorm gusts were around 75-80 mph given the nature of the observed wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A picture shared from social media showed a large pine tree uprooted by strong thunderstorm wind gusts.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A backdoor front entered northeastern NM during the early morning hours increasing surface moisture across the region. This added moisture along with daytime heating allowed isolated supercells to develop across southeastern Colfax and eastern Mora counties, moving southeast towards the Texas state line. Storms produced up to golf ball sized hail in Springer and near Roy, and wind gusts of up to 74 mph at Tucumcari.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Higher low-level moisture on July 13th and a backdoor cold front replenishing this moisture for July 14th and 15th combined with robust upper level wind shear produced three days of severe weather across eastern NM. Severe weather impacts were limited to northeastern NM on the 13th and 14th, becoming more widespread across northeastern and east-central NM on the 15th. There were a few thunderstorm wind gusts measured in the vicinity of the White Sands Missile Range on the 13th and 14th, likely from dry microbursts as the exception for the 13th and 14th. More substantial reports of damage and large hail occurred on the 15th ranging from broken skylights, flooding, accumulated hail, and a tornado. Thankfully, there were no reports of injuries or casualties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail broke three skylights, damage is an estimate. Half-dollar size hail reported alongside larger but shorter duration 2.75 inch hail. Hail persisted until approximately 5:10 pm MDT before quitting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Southerly flow brought elevated dewpoints in the 70s to southern New England leading to a heat advisory. All the heat and humidity led to good instability which, along with forcing from a strong mid level jet produced severe storms in Massachusetts and Connecticut and some flash flooding in Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Hatfield, there were wires down on Elm St.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level low off the coast of California helped funnel in subtropical moisture into the state resulting in the development of widespread showers and storms across central and eastern New Mexico June 5th and 6th. Reports of severe weather and flash flooding stretched from the Rio Grande Valley across portions of eastern NM on June 5th. These reports ranged from a landspout tornado near the Petroglyph National Monument and Nara Visa, NM to flash flooding. Another round of severe weather began in the afternoon of June 6th producing more widespread reports over the same area of the state. Reports ranged from burn scar flash flooding within the Hermits Peak/Calf Canyon burn scar and Santa Rosa, to large hail over parts of San Miguel County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fire Dept. in Cabo Lucero relayed secondary reports of quarter size hail and accumulated hail 4 to 6 inches deep. Location estimated to be at Mineral Hill based on radar. There were secondary reports of hail damage knocking out windows as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Sulf WSMR station measured a peak wind gust of 68 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain due to convective showers resulted in minor flooding of roads in Clackamas County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain and accumulating hail overwhelmed storm drains along Sunnyside Road near SE 117th Ave, leading to several inches of standing water on the road. Water was near the top of wheel wells of some vehicles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An extended period of stronger wind gusts generated some damage to trees and power lines across portions of Kauai, Oahu and Big Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree fell due to strong wind gusts. The tree was blocking two lanes of traffic on|Lanikuhana Ave. at Kamehameha Highway in Mililani.
