EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic cold front passed through the region on the 3rd ushering a cold and dry airmass along with windy conditions. Low temperatures on the 4th were well into the single digits to below zero in the higher elevations. This combined with the breezy to windy conditions resulted in dangerously low wind chills ranging from -10 to -20 across the Pocono Plateau.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Temperatures fell below zero across the Pocono Plateau. This combined with windy conditions resulted in dangerous wind chills ranging from -10 to -20.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A trough of low pressure moving eastward across California brought a plume of deep moisture to Arizona as well. The synoptic-scale ascent from the trough combined with the moisture allowed for periods of heavy rain over Arizona March 15 and 16.  Surface dewpoints were similar to summer time...in the 40s and 50s. The heavy rainfall, high snow levels, and deep snow pack combined to produce rapid snow melt and significant runoff into area waterways.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The West Clear Creek gauge near Camp Verde showed a 5-foot rise from 2.8 feet at noon on March 15 to a crest of 8.1 feet by 100 AM March 16. The water level returned to 2.8 feet by 9 AM on March 17.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A personal weather station measured a peak wind gust of 58 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Conditions were favorable again for widespread dense freezing fog to form over Northeast Montana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple episodes of intermittent dense fog with visibility of a quarter mile or less occurred at the Wolf Point Airport ASOS (KOLF). The first episode lasted for 11 3/4 hours from the late afternoon on the 18th to early morning on the 19th. The second episode lasted 2 1/2 hours on the morning of the 19th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the afternoon into early evening of January 30th and was mainly sleet mixed with some light snow. Estimated ice accretions of a light glaze of ice fell across the county. No sleet accumulation reports were available for the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Las Vegas Airport ASOS measured a high sustained wind of 55 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled front remains situated just to the northwest this morning with a light onshore flow near the surface while persistent southwesterly flow continues aloft. Cooler than normal mid-level temperatures created deeper instability that strengthened diurnally driven sea breeze storms as they develop along the east-coast sea breeze in the afternoon. Deeper moisture was across NE FL and portions of SE GA (generally south and east of Waycross) created more widespread storm coverage, especially along and west of the St Johns River basin as the sea breeze interacted with the river breeze. ||Strong to marginally severe wind gusts of 40-60 mph occurred. Marginal deep layer shear was around 20 kts which create a lower end hail threat. Locally heavy rainfall occurred that created mainly nuisance minor flood issues.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In late October, a winter storm dumped heavy snow in eastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota over a period of 2 days. Due to mesoscale forces at play, some areas received a foot of snow or more where the band stalled. In addition to heavy snow, there was also blowing snow, reducing visibility across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: COOP Station LBRM5 reports 8 inches of snow 2 miles east-southeast of Lake Bronson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A push of deep warm, southerly flow aloft combined with synoptic frontal lift over-top air starting out below freezing at ground level combined together to produce a mess of mixed precipitation types across much of Southcentral Alaska between 1/22 and 1/25.  Warm air with southerly winds gradually was able to work north and change wet snow over to rain as it filtered into interior valleys, with some mix with freezing rain observed briefly during the transition phase in a couple locations.  While precipitation amounts were generally light, aside from over a foot of snowfall observed in parts of the Susitna Valley, the sudden thaw and rain on top of snow and cold ground resulted in significant disruptions to travel and daily life for many residents across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 6 AM 1/24, Alaska Department of Transportation reported 14 inches of new snowfall along the Parks Highway between Mile Post 121 and 163 with difficult driving conditions.  The heaviest snowfall amounts were all focused on the northern end of the Susitna Valley, with areas farther south mixing with rain as warmer air intruded northwards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of weak lift aloft and temperatures near freezing below the snow growth layer of the the atmosphere was able to facilitate a period of light freezing rain and drizzle across parts of the Kenai Peninsula, Matanuska Valley and Anchorage area during the afternoon of 1/29.  While ice accumulation was very light, it did not take much to cause significant travel disruptions, with multiple ditched cars and accidents reported along the Glenn Highway between Palmer and Anchorage on the afternoon of 1/29.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Soldotna AWOS reported a mix of freezing rain and snow for a few hours during the afternoon of 1/29.  Little to no ice accumulation occurred based on reports available.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of weak lift aloft and temperatures near freezing below the snow growth layer of the the atmosphere was able to facilitate a period of light freezing rain and drizzle across parts of the Kenai Peninsula, Matanuska Valley and Anchorage area during the afternoon of 1/29.  While ice accumulation was very light, it did not take much to cause significant travel disruptions, with multiple ditched cars and accidents reported along the Glenn Highway between Palmer and Anchorage on the afternoon of 1/29.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Anchorage Police Department responded to a multi-vehicle crash on the inbound side of the Glenn Highway near Arctic Valley at around 4:30 PM AKST 1/29.  Officers reported very icy conditions on the Glenn Highway at the time.  A Seward Highway Facebook Group commenter mentioned very slick roadways along the same stretch of highway with multiple cars either rolled over or in ditches at around 7 PM AKST the same evening.  Freezing rain was also reported multiple times by Anchorage area mesonet sensors during the course of the afternoon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In late October, a winter storm dumped heavy snow in eastern North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota over a period of 2 days. Due to mesoscale forces at play, some areas received a foot of snow or more where the band stalled. In addition to heavy snow, there was also blowing snow, reducing visibility across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: CoCoRaHS station MN-KT-2 reports 6.2 inches of snow in Karlstad.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Thompson Cattle mesonet station measured a peak wind gust of 66 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the mid morning into afternoon hours of January 30th and was mainly sleet, mixed with some light snow and freezing rain. The CoCoRaHS station 5 miles SSE of Cassville reported 1.5 inches of sleet and snow, mainly in the form of sleet. There was also an estimated light glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly strengthening storm developed across the Northern Plains and into the western Great Lakes on March 16-17. An initial band of precipitation developed during the early morning hours of March 16 across northwest Iowa in the form of light rain or light freezing rain. However, a sharp fall in temperatures by midday and early afternoon forced a change to a few hours of snowfall accompanied by increasing northerly wind. Snow cover prior to the event was limited to areas north of Highway 18, where impacts from snow and blowing snow with winds of 45 to 55 mph were greatest during the afternoon of March 16, and again briefly on Friday, March 17 when reinvigorated winds brought very brief visibility of a quarter mile or less.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief period of light freezing rain resulted in a glaze of icing at the COOP site at Spencer. Northerly wind increased by the afternoon with gusts as high as 60 mph at Automated Surface Observing System site KSPW near Spencer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A push of deep warm, southerly flow aloft combined with synoptic frontal lift over-top air starting out below freezing at ground level combined together to produce a mess of mixed precipitation types across much of Southcentral Alaska between 1/22 and 1/25.  Warm air with southerly winds gradually was able to work north and change wet snow over to rain as it filtered into interior valleys, with some mix with freezing rain observed briefly during the transition phase in a couple locations.  While precipitation amounts were generally light, aside from over a foot of snowfall observed in parts of the Susitna Valley, the sudden thaw and rain on top of snow and cold ground resulted in significant disruptions to travel and daily life for many residents across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Alaska Department of Transportation reported a myriad of mixed precipitation starting out as snow, then mostly transitioning to rain as warm air above freezing filtered into valleys across the Copper River Basin from the south with time between 1/24 and 1/25.  Most locations did not receive significant snowfall or rainfall totals (no more than 6-7 inches of new snowfall prior to transition). Tazlina reported a brief period of freezing rain before switching over from snow to all rain during at around 5 AM 1/25.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong frontal system associated with a powerful low moving south of the Kamchatka Peninsula moved north into the western Aleutian Chain out of the North Pacific on 1/28, producing strong easterly winds as it crossed over into the southern Bering Sea.  The strongest winds by far were reported at Shemya, where peak gusts to 80 mph occurred during the late afternoon and evening hours of 1/28.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The AWOS sensor in Shemya began to report severe winds gusting above 75 mph around 6 PM AKST 1/28 and reported a peak gust of 82 mph at around 7 PM AKST 1/28 before winds began to decrease as the front pushed past to the north.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure centered well off the coast and strong high pressure building southward from eastern Canada resulted in the development of a steady onshore wind on June 3.  The pattern brought widespread moderate tidal flooding to the Delaware coast around the evening high tide.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread roadway flooding and some property flooding occurred in the tidal areas of Sussex County.  The tide gauge at Lewes reached 7.24 feet MLLW, the tide gauge at Rosedale Beach reached 5.74 feet MLLW, and the tide gauge at Indian River Inlet reached 5.33 feet MLLW.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The CWOP station GW0819 measured a high sustained wind of 47 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado developed just north of 1150th street and east of Highway 191 where it destroyed two barns and damaged others. The tornado track continued east with evidence of convergent flow pattern within the debris field and the cornfield as it tracked to the east.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A prolonged period of precipitation fell across the county, beginning during the early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingering into the very early morning of January 30th. No sleet accumulations were reported in the county. There was also an estimated light glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools also closed on January 30th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface cold front approaching from the north northwest in the afternoon was associated with a nearly west to east mid level shear axis streaking through the base of a large mid level trough whose low was centered over northern Quebec. Southwest flow ahead of this front drew in warm air and 60s dew points into the area, and this combined with strengthening mid level flow and upper divergence produced sufficient support for the development of numerous severe thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported down Thompson Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous supercell thunderstorms moved across parts of Logan, Morgan, Phillips, Weld and Washington counties during the evening and overnight, dropping baseball size hail or larger on several communities. Towns that received very large hail (baseball size or larger) included:  Akron, Iliff, Brush, Fort Morgan, Haxtun, Fleming, and Otis.  In addition to the large hail, an 82 mph wind gust was reported 6 SE of Holyoke and 81 mph wind gust was measured 8 S of Holyoke.  One large tree was downed by the wind.  Numerous reports of broken windows to homes along with extensive car damage.  Two tornadoes briefly touched down, but no damage was observed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Personal weather station measured a peak wind gust of 62 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the afternoon through early evening of January 30th and was mainly sleet. A CoCoRaHS report 4 miles southwest of Winona measured 0.8 inches of sleet accumulation, and a report 5 miles ESE of Eminence reported 0.6 inches of sleet. There was also an estimated light glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Prolonged drought conditions coupled with strong winds, low relative humidity, and receptive fuels contributed to critical fire weather conditions across the Texas Panhandle.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Yucca Fire started roughly 4 miles west of the dam in Hutchinson County. The fire was caused by a vehicle which resulted in a wildfire that burned 850 acres.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved from the Ohio River Valley on January 12th across central/northern New England on January 13th. Snow overspread northern New York during the evening of January 12th and continued overnight before exiting around midday on the 13th.||Snowfall totals across the region were generally 3 to 6 inches with some locally higher totals.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals were generally 3 to 6 inches across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A prolonged period of precipitation fell across the county, beginning during the early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingering into the very early morning of January 30th before briefly tapering off as sleet during the early morning of January 30th. No sleet accumulations were reported in the county. The Vichy ASOS reported a 30 hour flat ice accretion of 0.26 inches due to the prolonged freezing drizzle. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools also closed on January 30th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A widespread significant damaging wind storm tracked across nearly all of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa on the morning of July 12. These storms produced widespread winds of 60 to 80 mph, with embedded stronger downbursts with wind speeds up to 100 mph. The strongest measured wind gust was 82 mph in Dodge County NE, but some of the high-end straight line wind damage supports embedded wind speeds up to 100 mph.||This storm also produced a few embedded tornadoes. Some of the tornado tracks were only identified by narrow swaths of damage through mature cornfields, with minimal damage otherwise and peak wind speeds similar to the nearby downburst winds. All but one of the tornadoes was preceded by a Wireless Emergency Alert. There were 0 reported injuries or fatalities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public weather station measured a peak wind gust of 59 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain event after rain event continued to occur going into the month of June for the combined Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles. However, this time the higher amounts of rain fell over the Oklahoma Panhandle and northern Texas Panhandle. This wiped out the remaining drought in the area with the exception of far southeast Collingsworth County. Rivers and tributaries were starting to reach their banks and flood over them. The amount of rain that fell in May, leading into June, had caused the Canadian River to reach one of its highest points since the 1970s reaching 10.53 at the river gauge north of Amarillo just after midnight on June 1st. Thankfully the rains had shift northward to help eliminate much of the drought in the Oklahoma Panhandle, and as not to continue flooding areas across the the central to southern Texas Panhandle. Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sherman County started the month of June with Severe Drought (D2) conditions across the northeastern third of the county. A wet pattern continued through the early part of the month allowing for the area of D2 to improve to Moderate Drought (D1) by mid month. Rain events continued with the area of D1 improving to Abnormally Dry (D0) conditions by the third week. The county received a total of 3 to 6 over the course of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous short-wave trough interacted with an approaching low pressure system and associated warm frontal boundary to trigger clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms across west-central Illinois during the late afternoon of August 6th.  Due to enhanced low-level wind shear along and north of the warm front, many of the cells began rotating and spinning up occasional funnel clouds.  One of the cells intensified as it pushed into Sangamon County, producing a long-track tornado that was on the ground for over 25 miles from just north of Pawnee in far southeastern Sangamon County to southeast of Stonington in Christian County.  The tornado produced EF-1 damage along much of its path, peaking with EF-2 damage just south of Willeys in Christian County.  This particular thunderstorm cell dropped 2-inch diameter hail north of Taylorville and went on to produce a downburst with 80 mph wind gusts in far eastern Shelby County near Lake Mattoon.  The storms eventually congealed into a line as they pushed into eastern Illinois later in the evening, with scattered wind damage, hail, and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several tree branches were blown down.

Additional damage was noted about one-half mile to the northeast from the garage where a single-wide mobile home was significantly damaged. Little to no damage was found in a subdivision between these two points. Preliminary indications suggest straight-line winds of 80 to 90 mph.

A shortwave moving around a broader low in the Gulf of Alaska saw an embedded band of convective activity develop with strong cold air advection behind it, which resulted in an area of enhanced winds which tracked northward across the Inside Passage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Zarembo Island RAWS measured a peak gust of 55 mph at 1255pm AKDT. The burst of high winds then tracked northward across Sumner Strait and through Wrangell Narrows.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moving around a broader low in the Gulf of Alaska saw an embedded band of convective activity develop with strong cold air advection behind it, which resulted in an area of enhanced winds which tracked northward across the Inside Passage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The burst of high winds tracked northward from the Cape Fanshaw area, up Stephens Passage, and through Gastineau Channel. The FAA webcam at Grave Point, a little more than half way up the channel, measured a max sustained wind of 53 mph at 320pm AKDT (site does not measure gusts) and Point Arden saw a peak of 72 mph. This was followed by the AML Dock along Gastineau Channel in Juneau seeing a peak gust of 60 mph at 432pm and the airport, which includes a seaplane dock, seeing a peak gust of 71mph in the same hour. All of these locations observed these peak gusts after a sudden shift to the south from a light northerly.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: It was reported that the Greene County Highway Department cleared at least 20 trees from roadways. There were also approximately 1,300 power outages and numerous power poles down across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A shortwave moving around a broader low in the Gulf of Alaska saw an embedded band of convective activity develop with strong cold air advection behind it, which resulted in an area of enhanced winds which tracked northward across the Inside Passage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The burst of high winds tracked northward from the Juneau to Icy Strait area, and up through Lynn Canal. Winds peaked at 53 mph at Rocky Island and 51 mph at Little Island, then topping out at 59 mph at Eldred Rock. More impactful would have been that all of the observation points noted the peak gusts after a sudden shift to the south from a light northerly.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Mills Canyon RAWS measured a peak gust of 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving weather system brought a quick round of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to counties mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor across southern Missouri from around midday through mid to late afternoon on January 31st. This precipitation generally fell at any one location for around 2 to 3 hours before ending. While no measurements of snow, sleet, or ice was reported, observations did show light snow mixed with sleet and patchy freezing drizzle. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. A few isolated slide offs and crashes occurred during the morning and afternoon of February 1st due to the lingering slick spots on roadways despite no falling precipitation. Numerous schools south of Interstate 44 were closed for January 31st due to the precipitation forecast and road conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county during the afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A private weather station near Newkirk and Conchas Lake measured a high sustained wind speed of 45 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF1 tornado touched down near Tom Ben Road and Clifton Walker Road and moved NE. Multiple trees were uprooted and snapped in the area along with many branches broken. One home suffered minor rooftop damage and a cyclone fence was also knocked down. Further down the path, trees withstood heavier damage as winds blew up to 105 mph. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous short-wave trough interacted with an approaching low pressure system and associated warm frontal boundary to trigger clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms across west-central Illinois during the late afternoon of August 6th.  Due to enhanced low-level wind shear along and north of the warm front, many of the cells began rotating and spinning up occasional funnel clouds.  One of the cells intensified as it pushed into Sangamon County, producing a long-track tornado that was on the ground for over 25 miles from just north of Pawnee in far southeastern Sangamon County to southeast of Stonington in Christian County.  The tornado produced EF-1 damage along much of its path, peaking with EF-2 damage just south of Willeys in Christian County.  This particular thunderstorm cell dropped 2-inch diameter hail north of Taylorville and went on to produce a downburst with 80 mph wind gusts in far eastern Shelby County near Lake Mattoon.  The storms eventually congealed into a line as they pushed into eastern Illinois later in the evening, with scattered wind damage, hail, and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power line was blown down on East Lakeshore Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gust recorded at Coles County Memorial Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain event after rain event continued to occur going into the month of June for the combined Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles. However, this time the higher amounts of rain fell over the Oklahoma Panhandle and northern Texas Panhandle. This wiped out the remaining drought in the area with the exception of far southeast Collingsworth County. Rivers and tributaries were starting to reach their banks and flood over them. The amount of rain that fell in May, leading into June, had caused the Canadian River to reach one of its highest points since the 1970s reaching 10.53 at the river gauge north of Amarillo just after midnight on June 1st. Thankfully the rains had shift northward to help eliminate much of the drought in the Oklahoma Panhandle, and as not to continue flooding areas across the the central to southern Texas Panhandle. Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The majority of Lipscomb County started the month of June in Severe Drought (D2).  Rain events continued to slowly improve conditions through the month with D2 finally improving to Moderate Drought (D1) by the third week. The county received 3 to 8 of rain over the course of the month ending June in Abnormally Dry (D0) conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Storms developed in the afternoon as an upper-level short-wave moved across the area. Unorganized storms developed and produced a few hail reports with the largest reported hailstone being 2-inches near Creston in Madison County. There was also a single wind report of 65-mph near Thurston.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotter reported an estimated 65 mph wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: July 28 was a hot day as temperatures warmed into the mid-90s and low 100s. The highest observed temperature was 102 at Omaha Eppley Airfield. Heat indices that day ranged from 110 to 120 degrees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wahoo AWOS had a heat index near and above 110 for approximately 3-hours. The heat index peaked at 120.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of storms developed in central Nebraska where they merged and began to bow as it approached southeast Nebraska. The surging storms produced widespread wind damage downing trees, powerlines, and removed the roof from a hog barn. The strongest measured wind gust was 81 mph near Dorchester in Saline County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Falls City ASOS measured a peak wind gust of 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small tree was blown down near McDonald's on Eldorado Street in Decatur.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted north of the area and warm, moist, and unstable air flowed into the Mid-South during the morning hours of February 16, 2023.  A strong upper-level jet streak across the Great Lakes produced ascent across the Mid-South resulting in showers and thunderstorms with heavy rainfall and flash flooding across West Tennessee. Later in the day as the cold front approached, thunderstorms intensified and produced a few tornadoes across northeast Mississippi.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Old Dyer Yorkville Road was impassable due to flooding. There was widespread flooding in the Dyer area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree damage was noted across the wooded area between the Tombigbee River and the Tennessee Tombigbee Waterway west of Smithville. A swath of trees, approximately 100 yards wide, was uprooted or snapped just north of the end of Durrett Landing Road. The tornado began to weaken and occlude as it crossed Blue Water Creek, resulting in sporadic uprooted trees. Maximum winds were estimated at 90 mph with a maximum path width of 100 yards. Survey information aided by PERiLS drone surveillance.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted north of the area and warm, moist, and unstable air flowed into the Mid-South during the morning hours of February 16, 2023.  A strong upper-level jet streak across the Great Lakes produced ascent across the Mid-South resulting in showers and thunderstorms with heavy rainfall and flash flooding across West Tennessee. EVENT_NARRATIVE: The first identifiable damage from this tornado began on Friendship Road north northwest of Ramer. A detached metal and wood garage at this location was destroyed with numerous hardwood and softwood trees uprooted and snapped on the property. The tornado moved to the northeast and caused damage to a property on Teague Lane. Another large garage made of metal and wood was destroyed. A single-family residence on this property sustained a significant loss of roof material. The tornado moved eastward along Feddie Davis Road and caused additional hardwood and softwood tree damage. The tornado likely dissipated in a wooded area west of Highway 45.  Peak winds were estimated at 105 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving weather system brought a quick round of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to counties mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor across southern Missouri from around midday through mid to late afternoon on January 31st. This precipitation generally fell at any one location for around 2 to 3 hours before ending. While no measurements of snow, sleet, or ice was reported, observations did show light snow mixed with sleet and patchy freezing drizzle. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. A few isolated slide offs and crashes occurred during the morning and afternoon of February 1st due to the lingering slick spots on roadways despite no falling precipitation. Numerous schools south of Interstate 44 were closed for January 31st due to the precipitation forecast and road conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county from midday through mid afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st. Lingering ice on roadways during the afternoon of February 1st resulted in a car going down a snow covered hill and striking a tree, resulting in one injury.

The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county for a few hours during the afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st. Lingering ice on roadways on February 1st resulted in two separate incidents of a vehicle losing control on an icy roadway. The first accident in the morning had a vehicle lose control on the road, slide off the right side of the road, and strike a bluff. There was one injury in this one vehicle accident. The second accident in the afternoon had a vehicle lose control on the road, cross the center line, and strike another vehicle, resulting in one injury.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wake trough in trailing the departure of Hurricane Idalia lingering across NE FL. This feature combined with high tropical moisture, diurnal instability and the inland progressing west coast sea breeze produced localized heavy, flooding rainfall.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Street flooding was first reported around 2:46 pm near Main Street and near the 500 block of 32rd Avenue in Gainesville. A mesonet station about 2 miles SE of Gainesville measured 2.8 inches of rainfall in one hour at 2:45 pm. At 3:14 pm, Fire Rescue reported flash flooding was developing along NW 23rd Avenue in Gainesville. At 3:16 pm, at public weather station measured around 4.5 inches of rainfall about 1 mile SE of Gainesville since 1:45 pm. At 3:35 pm, a CoCoRaHS station about 2 miles SE of Gainesville measured 4.47 inches since 1:52 pm which created flooding conditions. By 4 pm, the county 911 dispatch center reported several roads within about a 10 block radius in Gainesville experienced significant flash flooding. There were some road closures at the time of the report.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving weather system brought a quick round of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to counties mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor across southern Missouri from around midday through mid to late afternoon on January 31st. This precipitation generally fell at any one location for around 2 to 3 hours before ending. While no measurements of snow, sleet, or ice was reported, observations did show light snow mixed with sleet and patchy freezing drizzle. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. A few isolated slide offs and crashes occurred during the morning and afternoon of February 1st due to the lingering slick spots on roadways despite no falling precipitation. Numerous schools south of Interstate 44 were closed for January 31st due to the precipitation forecast and road conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county from midday through mid afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during from midday through the afternoon of January 30th and was almost all sleet with a small amount of freezing rain. A CoCoRaHS report 2 miles east of Odin measured 0.7 inches of sleet accumulation. There was also an estimated light glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled front remains situated just to the northwest this morning with a light onshore flow near the surface while persistent southwesterly flow continues aloft. Cooler than normal mid-level temperatures created deeper instability that strengthened diurnally driven sea breeze storms as they develop along the east-coast sea breeze in the afternoon. Deeper moisture was across NE FL and portions of SE GA (generally south and east of Waycross) created more widespread storm coverage, especially along and west of the St Johns River basin as the sea breeze interacted with the river breeze. ||Strong to marginally severe wind gusts of 40-60 mph occurred. Marginal deep layer shear was around 20 kts which create a lower end hail threat. Locally heavy rainfall occurred that created mainly nuisance minor flood issues.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant roof damage occurred due to winds at 330 Main Street.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mesonet site at JFRD Station 40 measured a wind gust of 46 mph.

Later in the day as the cold front approached, thunderstorms intensified and produced a few tornadoes across northeast Mississippi.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain event after rain event continued to occur going into the month of June for the combined Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles. However, this time the higher amounts of rain fell over the Oklahoma Panhandle and northern Texas Panhandle. This wiped out the remaining drought in the area with the exception of far southeast Collingsworth County. Rivers and tributaries were starting to reach their banks and flood over them. The amount of rain that fell in May, leading into June, had caused the Canadian River to reach one of its highest points since the 1970s reaching 10.53 at the river gauge north of Amarillo just after midnight on June 1st. Thankfully the rains had shift northward to help eliminate much of the drought in the Oklahoma Panhandle, and as not to continue flooding areas across the the central to southern Texas Panhandle. Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small area of Severe Drought (D2) existed in the northeast corner of Wheeler County at the beginning of the month. Several back to back rain events occurred in the beginning of the month lead to much of the county to rid itself of drought by mid month.  The county had received 8 to 12 of rain for the entire month.

Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several rain events continued through much of June improving conditions to Moderate Drought (D3) by the third week. The county received around 4 to 8 of rain over the course of the month leaving the county in Abnormally Dry (D0) conditions at months end.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few late-season strong thunderstorms developed and moved across Midland/Odessa during the evening. Producing accumulating hail up to the size of nickels, mainly near the east side of Odessa.

Rain event after rain event continued to occur going into the month of June for the combined Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles. However, this time the higher amounts of rain fell over the Oklahoma Panhandle and northern Texas Panhandle. This wiped out the remaining drought in the area with the exception of far southeast Collingsworth County. Rivers and tributaries were starting to reach their banks and flood over them. The amount of rain that fell in May, leading into June, had caused the Canadian River to reach one of its highest points since the 1970s reaching 10.53 at the river gauge north of Amarillo just after midnight on June 1st. Thankfully the rains had shift northward to help eliminate much of the drought in the Oklahoma Panhandle, and as not to continue flooding areas across the the central to southern Texas Panhandle. Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: About a third of the western portion of the county started the month of June with Severe Drought (D1) conditions. An area of D2 also existed across the far northern conditions up against the Oklahoma Panhandle. Continued rain events through the month had most of the areas of D2 improving to D1 by mid month. The exception being the far southwest corner of the county that did not improve to D1 until the third week. Much of the county received 5 to 8 of rain over the course of the month allowing for the county to end the month with Abnormally Dry (D0) conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous supercell thunderstorms moved across parts of Logan, Morgan, Phillips, Weld and Washington counties during the evening and overnight, dropping baseball size hail or larger on several communities. Towns that received very large hail (baseball size or larger) included:  Akron, Iliff, Brush, Fort Morgan, Haxtun, Fleming, and Otis.  In addition to the large hail, an 82 mph wind gust was reported 6 SE of Holyoke and 81 mph wind gust was measured 8 S of Holyoke.  One large tree was downed by the wind.  Numerous reports of broken windows to homes along with extensive car damage.  Two tornadoes briefly touched down, but no damage was observed.

A complex of showers and thunderstorms moved southeast through portions of the Texas Panhandle during the overnight period of June 7th-8th. This complex moved fairly quickly only dropping 0.5 up to around 0.75 of rain. However, Amarillo had already seen its storage and playa lakes at capacity. This system sent many areas near lakes into some historical flooding with residents being evacuated from some of these areas early in the morning on the 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Virginia Circle area was evacuated due to flooding. An estimated four feet of water  was in the parking lot of the Oakridge  Apartments as well as some commercial buildings in the area  were flooded. An estimated 130 people and 20  pets were evacuated per Amarillo Fire Department.  Multiple high water rescues were conducted by the fire department in order to evacuate residents. Multiple cars were swept away by the flood waters, ending up in ditches and submerged in water. Areas between Georgia Street and Paramount Boulevard, and from Duniven Circle area to Duncan Street were covered by standing water. Loop 335 east and westbound service road at Western as well as I-40  service road at Western were closed due to water over the roadway.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large Rocky Mountain trough and attendant jet streak brought westerly high winds to the Guadalupe and Delaware Mountains.
As a large upper-level trough moved into the Great Plains, strong westerly winds overspread the higher elevations of the Guadalupe and Delaware Mountains.

Large clusters of intense thunderstorms sagged southeastward across southern Illinois during the night. A few of these clusters produced multiple reports of wind damage, especially in southeast Illinois to the east of Interstate 57. The storms occurred ahead of a surface low pressure center over west central Illinois. A surface boundary extended southeast into the lower Ohio Valley. Despite loss of daytime heating, the storms maintained their intensity with the aid of a 500 mb jet streak that rotated into the base of a trough over southeast Missouri.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-1 tornado began in northern Somerset County near Bernardsville along the NJ Transit Line just to the southwest of the intersection of Minebrook Rd and Old Quarry Rd. There it dropped numerous trees onto the NJ Transit Line and snapped the trunk|of around ten trees. As it moved to the northeast, the storm uprooted two maple trees along Mine Brook behind the Rose Bowl Baseball field that were on a slight embankment. The storm continued to move towards the northeast into Bernardsville|where it produced tree damage along Laurel Lane and snapped the trunk of a tree that appeared not to be fully healthy. The tornado then started to move more towards the north following Mine Brook through Bernardsville producing damage from Timber|Rock Trail to Anderson Hill Rd where it snapped the trunk of a pine tree that ended up falling on a vehicle. The peak width of the tornado was over this area where the damage path was approximately Four hundred seventy five yards between the damage from Timber Rock Trail to Anderson Hill Rd. Additional damage was found along the path of Anderson Hill Rd moving to the north towards the intersection of Seney Dr and Anderson Hill Rd where numerous trees were brought down with at least two ending up on power lines. At the intersection of Anderson Hill Rd and Rolling Hill Rd, another|large tree had its trunk snapped. However, the interior of the tree was determined not to be healthy, so the expected winds based on the DoD were reduced significantly. As the storm was starting to occlude and weaken, it took down several more trees along|Old Fort Road including uprooting multiple trees with wide, but shallow root systems. The tornado then dissipated as the storm moved further to the northeast. The EF-1 rating is primarily based on the number of trees with snapped trunks with the highest|concentration in a single location being along the NJ transit line. This is where the damage indicator of hardwood trees with degree of damage of trunks snapped produced an expected wind speed of one hundred five mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain event after rain event continued to occur going into the month of June for the combined Oklahoma and Texas Panhandles. However, this time the higher amounts of rain fell over the Oklahoma Panhandle and northern Texas Panhandle. This wiped out the remaining drought in the area with the exception of far southeast Collingsworth County. Rivers and tributaries were starting to reach their banks and flood over them. The amount of rain that fell in May, leading into June, had caused the Canadian River to reach one of its highest points since the 1970s reaching 10.53 at the river gauge north of Amarillo just after midnight on June 1st. Thankfully the rains had shift northward to help eliminate much of the drought in the Oklahoma Panhandle, and as not to continue flooding areas across the the central to southern Texas Panhandle. Although some flooding did start to manifest in the north during the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The majority of Texas County started the month of June in Severe Drought (D2) conditions with small areas of Moderate Drought (D1) in the northwest and southeast corners. A wet pattern continued across much of the area going into June with D2 improving to D1 by mid month. The county received a monthly rainfall of 3 to 8 allowing much of the county to end June with Abnormally Dry (D0) conditions.

Isolated to scattered thunderstorms developed in the Adirondacks and moved into the Champlain Valley.  A few storms produced locally large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous supercell thunderstorms moved across parts of Logan, Morgan, Phillips, Weld and Washington counties during the evening and overnight, dropping baseball size hail or larger on several communities. Towns that received very large hail (baseball size or larger) included:  Akron, Iliff, Brush, Fort Morgan, Haxtun, Fleming, and Otis.  In addition to the large hail, an 82 mph wind gust was reported 6 SE of Holyoke and 81 mph wind gust was measured 8 S of Holyoke.  One large tree was downed by the wind.  Numerous reports of broken windows to homes along with extensive car damage.  Two tornadoes briefly touched down, but no damage was observed.

Very heavy rain occurred across some areas of northeast Colorado from June 11th until the early hours of June 12th with flash flooding in some areas.  The worst areas were south and southeast of Fort Collins towards Timnath and Windsor and in the Milliken area.  Locations in these areas received from 3.0 to  5.5 inches of rain.  Another area was located in and near Limon where significant flash flooding occurred along with a few water rescues.  Several roads were closed due to flash flooding north of CO-86 and west of I-70. Rainfall amounts in the these areas ranged from 2.4 to 3.7 inches. Severe thunderstorms produced large hail, from quarter to ping pong ball size.  The hail piled anywhere from 4 to 8 inches deep along roads and highways in Elbert and Lincoln counties.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broken line of thunderstorms moved southeast across parts of southeast Missouri. A few of these storms produced strong winds, including isolated wind damage at Poplar Bluff. During the peak heating hours in the mid to late afternoon, thunderstorms gradually increased in coverage along a weak surface boundary over southeast Missouri. Wind shear was weak, but strong instability and high precipitable water values resulted in a wet microburst. Mixed-layer cape ranged from 2500 to 3500 J/kg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving weather system brought a quick round of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to counties mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor across southern Missouri from around midday through mid to late afternoon on January 31st. This precipitation generally fell at any one location for around 2 to 3 hours before ending. While no measurements of snow, sleet, or ice was reported, observations did show light snow mixed with sleet and patchy freezing drizzle. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. A few isolated slide offs and crashes occurred during the morning and afternoon of February 1st due to the lingering slick spots on roadways despite no falling precipitation. Numerous schools south of Interstate 44 were closed for January 31st due to the precipitation forecast and road conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county from midday through mid afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the mid morning through afternoon of January 30th and was mainly sleet mixed with some light snow. A CoCoRaHS report 1 mile southeast of Republic measured 0.4 inches of sleet and snow accumulation, mainly in the form of sleet. The NWS Springfield observation reported 0.33 inches of flat ice accretion from the 28 hours of freezing drizzle and 0.3 inches of sleet. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st. Multiple crashes and slide offs occurred across the county, mainly occurring prior to the second round of precipitation. 17 separate crashes were reported across the county, involving 17 total vehicles and 10 total injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quick moving weather system brought a quick round of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to counties mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor across southern Missouri from around midday through mid to late afternoon on January 31st. This precipitation generally fell at any one location for around 2 to 3 hours before ending. While no measurements of snow, sleet, or ice was reported, observations did show light snow mixed with sleet and patchy freezing drizzle. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed that this light precipitation was enough to partly cover or completely cover roads and result in slick conditions into the evening commute on January 31st, and some lingering slick spots on roads into February 1st. A few isolated slide offs and crashes occurred during the morning and afternoon of February 1st due to the lingering slick spots on roadways despite no falling precipitation. Numerous schools south of Interstate 44 were closed for January 31st due to the precipitation forecast and road conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving system brought a brief mix of light sleet, light snow, and patchy freezing drizzle to the county during the mid to late afternoon on January 31st. No measurements of snow, sleet, or ice were reported. The Missouri Department of Transportation traveler map showed roads becoming covered and slick, with slick roads lingering into the evening commute and patchy slick spots into February 1st.

Numerous supercell thunderstorms moved across parts of Logan, Morgan, Phillips, Weld and Washington counties during the evening and overnight, dropping baseball size hail or larger on several communities. Towns that received very large hail (baseball size or larger) included:  Akron, Iliff, Brush, Fort Morgan, Haxtun, Fleming, and Otis.  In addition to the large hail, an 82 mph wind gust was reported 6 SE of Holyoke and 81 mph wind gust was measured 8 S of Holyoke.  One large tree was downed by the wind.  Numerous reports of broken windows to homes along with extensive car damage.  Two tornadoes briefly touched down, but no damage was observed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Tucumcari Airport ASOS measured a peak wind gust of 75 mph.

CZ_NAME: SAN BERNARDINO AND RIVERSIDE COUNTY VALLEYS - THE INLAND EMPIRE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Ramona Wildfire burned 350 acres, prompting evacuation orders for populated areas in Riverside County. The fire ignited on May 22 and was 100% contained by 8:00 PM on May 25.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 350 acre vegetation fire burned in the San Jacinto Valley in Riverside County from the afternoon on May 22 through the evening on May 25. The ignition occurred in the Ramona Expressway and North Warren Road area. The fire approached residential area as well as dairy farms, prompting evacuation orders and warnings through the late evening on May 22 before being lifted. The fire was 100% contained by 8:00 PM on May 25.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: February saw more wetter than normal conditions across the western half of NM with drier than normal conditions persistent through much of the eastern plains of NM. There was very little change in the drought conditions however. By month's end, 16 percent of the state was in severe to extreme drought, of which about 3 percent was extreme drought.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe to extreme drought conditions from October 2022 persisted through February 2023.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An abnormally cold upper level winter storm system impacted northern and central NM on February 15, 2023. Widespread heavy snow was reported across western, northern, and central NM. Impacts began late in the day on February 14, 2023, peaking in intensity during the morning of February 15, 2023 before the storm exited late in the day. Snow accumulations of over a foot up to 15 inches were reported along the Continental Divide and northern mountain peaks. Blowing snow reducing visibility and snow packed roads caused reports of severe winter travel and forced some roads to be closed. These included I-25 at Raton Pass and U.S. Highway 64 from Raton to Clayton. Strong winds were also present with this storm system, although less pronounced compared to the prior storm system. A lone high wind report at the Roswell Airport was observed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow impacted the Chuska Mountains where there was an estimated 13 inches of snow at a SNOTEL site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense supercell thunderstorm initially developed near Sidney in Cheyenne County early in the afternoon on 6/21, producing up to baseball sized hail in and around Sidney, as well as a brief tornado near the community of Lorenzo between 1:00 PM and 2:00 PM MDT. This initial activity generally drifted to the west-southwest, and eventually to the northwest due to weak steering winds aloft. Numerous additional thunderstorms developed through the afternoon and evening, with multiple clusters of strong to marginally severe storms with occasional reports of up to quarter sized hail and 60 MPH wind gusts across the western Nebraska Panhandle.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported 2-inch diameter hail on the east side of the city of Sidney.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep southwesterly flow aloft prevailed across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley on January 30th-February 2nd, ahead of a strong upper level low pressure system that drifted through Southern California, the Desert Southwest into Northern Mexico. Meanwhile, a strong but shallow arctic cold front shifted south through the Southern Plains on January 29th-30th, before slowing significantly in the higher terrain of the Ouachitas of Southeast Oklahoma and Western Arkansas. Weak upper level disturbances embedded in this flow ahead of the low resulted in widespread sleet and freezing rain across much of the Southern Plains given the warm air above this shallow, freezing air mass, with areas of light freezing rain affecting portions of East Texas, extreme Southeast Oklahoma, and Southwest Arkansas on January 30th-February 2nd. Ice accumulations of one-quarter inch were observed across Hempstead and Nevada Counties in Southwest Arkansas, with ice accretion noted on trees and power lines, as well as significant icing on bridges and overpasses. Numerous large limbs were snapped off of trees due to the weight of the ice, with several trees downed on homes in Prescott (Nevada County). ||The following are freezing rain reports across Hempstead and Nevada Counties in Southwest Arkansas:||Hempstead County: Hope: 0.25 inches.|Nevada County: Prescott: 0.25 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Sierra Blanca Airport AWOS measured a peak gust of 74 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous short-wave trough interacted with an approaching low pressure system and associated warm frontal boundary to trigger clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms across west-central Illinois during the late afternoon of August 6th.  Due to enhanced low-level wind shear along and north of the warm front, many of the cells began rotating and spinning up occasional funnel clouds.  One of the cells intensified as it pushed into Sangamon County, producing a long-track tornado that was on the ground for over 25 miles from just north of Pawnee in far southeastern Sangamon County to southeast of Stonington in Christian County.  The tornado produced EF-1 damage along much of its path, peaking with EF-2 damage just south of Willeys in Christian County.  This particular thunderstorm cell dropped 2-inch diameter hail north of Taylorville and went on to produce a downburst with 80 mph wind gusts in far eastern Shelby County near Lake Mattoon.  The storms eventually congealed into a line as they pushed into eastern Illinois later in the evening, with scattered wind damage, hail, and flash flooding.
