An abnormally cold upper level winter storm system impacted northern and central NM on February 15, 2023. Widespread heavy snow was reported across western, northern, and central NM. Impacts began late in the day on February 14, 2023, peaking in intensity during the morning of February 15, 2023 before the storm exited late in the day. Snow accumulations of over a foot up to 15 inches were reported along the Continental Divide and northern mountain peaks. Blowing snow reducing visibility and snow packed roads caused reports of severe winter travel and forced some roads to be closed. These included I-25 at Raton Pass and U.S. Highway 64 from Raton to Clayton. Strong winds were also present with this storm system, although less pronounced compared to the prior storm system. A lone high wind report at the Roswell Airport was observed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow impacted the eastern edge of the zone near Taos where there was a nearby report of 8 inches in Valdez. There were various other snow reports of 2 to 5 inches of snow from Taos to Questa.

CZ_NAME: SOUTHERN MONTEREY BAY AND BIG SUR COAST
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Four divers off Fanshell Beach in the Pebble Beach area were dragged out to sea by a rip current. Three of the divers were able to return to shore safely, but the other perished in the water.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Search and Rescue team were unable to locate the diver who was swept out to sea by a rip current. Point Sur Buoy (Station 46239) measured average seas between 8 and 9 feet that day. Nearby Cabrillo Point buoy (Station 46240) in Monterey Bay, measured average seas 3 to 4 feet. Winds were not measured by the buoys, but the official forecast for the coastal zone from Point Pinos to Point Piedras Blancas called for NW winds 10-20 kt, with gusts up to 30 kt.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On January 4th to the 5th, a strong atmospheric river combined with a bomb cyclone led to widespread heavy rain, damaging wind gusts, and high surf across the Bay Area and Central Coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A redwood tree fell onto a double wide mobile home on the 2800 block of Joy Road in Occidental, killing a 2-year old boy when the tree pinned him down on the couch in the home's living room. Rescue crews were called around 5:15 PM, and performed CPR on the boy, but the boy died at the scene.

Light snow and snow showers redeveloped and moved across Vermont Friday before ending by evening.||Snowfall amounts across Vermont ranged from 1 to 3 inches in southern VT, 3 to 6 inches in central Vermont with 6 to 12 inches in northern VT, especially in the higher elevations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals ranged from 2 to 5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic air mass combined with a low pressure trough hanging over the area resulted in moderate lake effect snow accumulation and periods of considerable blowing snow across the Keweenaw Peninsula from the 1st through the 2nd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Observers reported moderate lake effect snow accumulation of approximately 4-5 inches per day on the 1st and 2nd with considerable blowing snow on the 2nd due to northwest winds gusting over 40 mph at times.

CZ_NAME: JOHNSON AND BARTLETT MESAS INCLUDING RATON PASS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A private citizen weather station near Des Moines measured a peak gust of 64 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous short-wave trough interacted with an approaching low pressure system and associated warm frontal boundary to trigger clusters of strong to severe thunderstorms across west-central Illinois during the late afternoon of August 6th.  Due to enhanced low-level wind shear along and north of the warm front, many of the cells began rotating and spinning up occasional funnel clouds.  One of the cells intensified as it pushed into Sangamon County, producing a long-track tornado that was on the ground for over 25 miles from just north of Pawnee in far southeastern Sangamon County to southeast of Stonington in Christian County.  The tornado produced EF-1 damage along much of its path, peaking with EF-2 damage just south of Willeys in Christian County.  This particular thunderstorm cell dropped 2-inch diameter hail north of Taylorville and went on to produce a downburst with 80 mph wind gusts in far eastern Shelby County near Lake Mattoon.  The storms eventually congealed into a line as they pushed into eastern Illinois later in the evening, with scattered wind damage, hail, and flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado crossed from Sangamon County into far western Christian County just north of the intersection of Pawnee-New City Road and Skaggs Road at 6:13 PM CDT.  It continued east-southeastward across Sangchris Lake, damaging a home near the lakeshore and causing extensive tree damage before passing just north of Tovey and Kincaid.  The tornado crossed Route 29 southeast of Sharpsburg and tracked over mainly open fields between Routes 29 and 48.  It then strengthened and caused EF-2 damage 2 miles south of Willeys along 1600 East Road just south of 1600 North Road where it demolished about 2/3 of a house.  The tornado continued east-southeastward, then dissipated near North 2300 East Road about a half mile north of 1500 North Road at 7:03 PM CDT.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe to locally extreme drought persisted through the month of February although conditions did show some improvement given continued wet conditions through the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe drought occurred in Crawford county in February although wet conditions limited the severe conditions to the far west of the county by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep southwesterly flow aloft prevailed across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley on January 30th-February 2nd, ahead of a strong upper level low pressure system that drifted through Southern California, the Desert Southwest into Northern Mexico. Meanwhile, a strong but shallow arctic cold front shifted south through the Southern Plains on the January 29th-30th, before slowing significantly in the higher terrain of the Ouachitas of Southeast Oklahoma and Western Arkansas. Weak upper level disturbances embedded in this flow ahead of the low resulted in widespread sleet and freezing rain across much of the Southern Plains given the warm air above this shallow, freezing air mass, with areas of light freezing rain affecting portions of East Texas, extreme Southeast Oklahoma, and Southwest Arkansas from January 30th-February 2nd. Ice accumulations near or in excess of one-quarter inch was observed across the western sections of East Texas as well as Hempstead and Nevada Counties in Southwest Arkansas, with ice accretion of 0.25-0.50 inches noted on trees and power lines, as well as significant icing on bridges and overpasses. ||The following are freezing rain reports across various counties in East Texas:||Red River County: Detroit: 0.40 inches, Bogota: 0.25 inches.|Franklin County: Mount Vernon: 0.25 inches.|Wood County: Lake Fork: 0.25 inches.|Smith County: 7SE Lindale: 0.25 inches, 2S Tyler: 0.20 inches, 3SE Noonday: 0.10 inches.

An intense supercell thunderstorm initially developed near Sidney in Cheyenne County early in the afternoon on 6/21, producing up to baseball sized hail in and around Sidney, as well as a brief tornado near the community of Lorenzo between 1:00 PM and 2:00 PM MDT. This initial activity generally drifted to the west-southwest, and eventually to the northwest due to weak steering winds aloft. Numerous additional thunderstorms developed through the afternoon and evening, with multiple clusters of strong to marginally severe storms with occasional reports of up to quarter sized hail and 60 MPH wind gusts across the western Nebraska Panhandle.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 59 MPH was recorded at the ASOS sensor at the Sidney Airport (KSNY).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On January 17th and 18th, two separate landslides impacted the ACE commuter rail track between Fremont and Sunol, forcing the cancellation of service until the 23rd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two separate landslides, one on Tuesday the 17th at 8:30 AM, and another on Wednesday the 18th during the morning, resulted in the suspension of ACE commuter rail service until the 23rd. The first landslide forced the ACE trains to stop on the section of rail parallel to Niles Canyon Road, with the train brought back to Pleasanton and bus bridges bringing passengers to their final destination.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An inside slider brought an additional round of snow to the region on January 29th. The cold, easterly flow with this system allowed for the better orographic enhancement of modest mid-level moisture east of the Sierra crest.  Parts of far western NV and northeast California received the most snowfall, with 1-4 inches of storm total snow across the greater Reno and Carson City area as well as areas south into the Carson valley of Douglas County along US-395. Areas across northeast California east of the Sierra Crest received around 1-3 inches of accumulating snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public located at June Mountain Ski base reported storm total snowfall of 10 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: One last colder and quick-moving storm wrapped up the current active storm cycle during the overnight/early morning hours of January 18-19. This winter system produced 4-10 inches of accumulating snow across much of the Sierra and Lake Tahoe Basin with lesser amounts across northeast California and around the Reno-Sparks area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public at the Mount Rose Ski Base, and a trained spotter located 1.0 mi NNW of Incline Village, NV, reported 24 hour snowfall totals of 9.0 and 7.5 inches respectively.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The strongest winter storm of December finished up early on New Year's day.  This atmospheric river (AR) enhanced winter storm initially produced very high snow levels near 9000 feet on 30 December with heavy rainfall continuing below that elevation.  But colder air and enhanced forcing, coupled with the final push of extensive moisture worked in unison to rapidly drop snow levels to most valley floors (above 4000 feet) during the morning of New Years Eve that carried over into the overnight hours through early morning New Years day. Some foothill areas received 1-2 feet plus of new snow with Sierra snowfall totals generally ranging from 18-30 inches below 7000 feet. Higher Sierra areas and passes received 3-4 feet plus of accumulating snow above 7000 feet before the winter system exited the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: COCORAHS Station (CA-NV-51) located 2.0 mi N Truckee, CA, and CO-OP observer located 1.0 mi SSW of Boca Reservoir, CA, reported 24 hour heavy rainfall totals of 5.57 and 4.62 inches respectively during the period from 12/31/22 through 1/1/23.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: From January 8th to January 9th, a strong atmospheric river led to widespread flooding across the San Francisco Bay Area and Central Coast. This was followed by convection on the 10th that resulted in flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Roadway flooding was reported along Mark West Creek near the communities of Forestville and Trenton. A 43-year old woman from Ukiah was recovered on the 10th after her car got stuck in floodwaters. She had called 911 to report that her car was taking on water on Trenton-Healdsburg Road. The call cut out, and Sonoma County Fire sent swift water rescue gear around 10:10 AM on the 9th. A helicopter from the Sonoma County Sheriff's office was also involved. The search was called off at sunset, and by the morning of the 10th, the vehicle was found sitting in 8 to 10 feet of floodwaters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An inside slider brought an additional round of snow to the region on January 29th. The cold, easterly flow with this system allowed for the better orographic enhancement of modest mid-level moisture east of the Sierra crest.  Parts of far western NV and northeast California received the most snowfall, with 1-4 inches of storm total snow across the greater Reno and Carson City area as well as areas south into the Carson valley of Douglas County along US-395. Areas across northeast California east of the Sierra Crest received around 1-3 inches of accumulating snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station (MTH03) Mammoth Mountain located 1.7 mi S of the Mammoth Mountain Ski Summit, CA, reported a maximum wind gusts of 65 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: One last colder and quick-moving storm wrapped up the current active storm cycle during the overnight/early morning hours of January 18-19. This winter system produced 4-10 inches of accumulating snow across much of the Sierra and Lake Tahoe Basin with lesser amounts across northeast California and around the Reno-Sparks area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public located at the Heavenly Ski Base and Palisades Tahoe Ski Base both reported 24 hour snow amounts of 8.0 and 9.0  inches respectively.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep southwesterly flow aloft prevailed across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley on January 30th-31st, ahead of a strong upper level low pressure system that drifted through Southern California, the Desert Southwest into Northern Mexico. Meanwhile, a strong but shallow arctic cold front shifted south through the Southern Plains on the January 29th-30th, before slowing significantly in the higher terrain of the Ouachitas of Southeast Oklahoma and Western Arkansas. Weak upper level disturbances embedded in this flow ahead of the low resulted in widespread sleet and freezing rain across much of the Southern Plains given the warm air above this shallow, freezing air mass, with areas of light freezing rain affecting portions of East Texas, extreme Southeast Oklahoma, and Southwest Arkansas on January 30th-February 2nd. Temperatures through the period ranged from a couple of degrees either side of the freezing mark across portions of Southwest Arkansas, with light ice accumulations ranging from a glaze up to 0.15 inches, mainly on elevated objects such as bridges and overpasses, trees and power lines. ||The following are freezing rain reports across various counties in Southwest Arkansas:||Sevier County: De Queen: 0.01 inches.|Howard County: Nashville: 0.01 inches.|Lafayette County: Lewisville: 0.10 inches.|Columbia County: Waldo: 0.15 inches.|Union County: El Dorado: 0.09 inches.

Temperatures through the period ranged from a couple of degrees either side of the freezing mark across portions of Southwest Arkansas, with light ice accumulations ranging from a glaze up to 0.15 inches, mainly on elevated objects such as bridges and overpasses, trees and power lines. ||The following are freezing rain reports across various counties in Southwest Arkansas:||Sevier County: De Queen: 0.01 inches.|Howard County: Nashville: 0.01 inches.|Lafayette County: Lewisville: 0.10 inches.|Columbia County: Waldo: 0.15 inches.|Union County: El Dorado: 0.09 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Ophelia tracked northward across east central North Carolina and up through central Virginia from early Saturday morning, September 23rd into early Sunday morning, September 24th. The storm produced bands of heavy rain across much of the Lower Maryland Eastern Shore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall total of 3.55 inches was reported at (0.9 ENE) Crisfield.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stronger winter storm produced several waves of new snow and high winds that impacted the region during the third week of January. A relatively long-duration atmospheric river from 9-11 January supported forcing and moisture for the first in the series of winter systems that brought heavy Sierra snowfall with accumulations ranging from 3-6 feet across the Sierra Crest. The heaviest snowfall occurred in Mono County over the 3-day period with heavy, unrelenting snowfall that forced a prolonged closure of US-395 from Bridgeport to Bishop from late morning January 9th through the afternoon January 11th.  On January 9th, heavy rain across the Lake Tahoe Basin changed to heavy snow below 7000 ft, leading to snowfall totals ranging from 8-20 inches through January 11th. Over 2 feet of snowfall was observed in parts of northeast California above 5000 feet. On January 9th mostly rain fell across western Nevada with storm total precipitation amounts ranging between 0.75-2 inches across much of Douglas, Carson City, southern Washoe, Mineral, and Lyon counties. The heavier rainfall across those contributed to a major rockfall and subsequently lead to an extended road closure on SR-208 in Wilson Canyon (Figure 4). Reports of areal flooding included I-80 near Lockwood, NN, Geiger Grade at Toll Rd in the Virginia City highlands, and along US-395 south of Reno with flooding from Steamboat Creek spilling over Towne Road. The changeover to snow in western Nevada arrived during the morning commute on January 10th which led to several related traffic incidents that included a 19-car pile-up on the Galena Bridge on I-580.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet Station (NV DOT-REV) located along US-95 near Walker Lake, NV reported a peak wind gust from the south at 75 mph at 11:57 AM.

The strongest winter storm of December finished up early on New Year's day.  This atmospheric river (AR) enhanced winter storm initially produced very high snow levels near 9000 feet on 30 December with heavy rainfall continuing below that elevation.  But colder air and enhanced forcing, coupled with the final push of extensive moisture worked in unison to rapidly drop snow levels to most valley floors (above 4000 feet) during the morning of New Years Eve that carried over into the overnight hours through early morning New Years day. Some foothill areas received 1-2 feet plus of new snow with Sierra snowfall totals generally ranging from 18-30 inches below 7000 feet. Higher Sierra areas and passes received 3-4 feet plus of accumulating snow above 7000 feet before the winter system exited the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public located at Mammoth Mountain Ski base and June Mountain Ski base reported storm total snowfall of 54 and 43 inches respectively during the period from 12/31/22 through 1/1/23.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep southwesterly flow aloft prevailed across the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley on January 30th-February 2nd, ahead of a strong upper level low pressure system that drifted through Southern California, the Desert Southwest into Northern Mexico. Meanwhile, a strong but shallow arctic cold front shifted south through the Southern Plains on January 29th-30th, before slowing significantly in the higher terrain of the Ouachitas of Southeast Oklahoma and Western Arkansas. Weak upper level disturbances embedded in this flow ahead of the low resulted in widespread sleet and freezing rain across much of the Southern Plains given the warm air above this shallow, freezing air mass, with areas of light freezing rain affecting portions of East Texas, extreme Southeast Oklahoma, and Southwest Arkansas on January 30th-February 2nd. Ice accumulations of one-quarter inch were observed across Hempstead and Nevada Counties in Southwest Arkansas, with ice accretion noted on trees and power lines, as well as significant icing on bridges and overpasses. Numerous large limbs were snapped off of trees due to the weight of the ice, with several trees downed on homes in Prescott (Nevada County). ||The following are freezing rain reports across Hempstead and Nevada Counties in Southwest Arkansas:||Hempstead County: Hope: 0.25 inches.|Nevada County: Prescott: 0.25 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Adequate precipitation in June across western, far southwestern and portions of north central Nebraska, led to some improvement in drought conditions in these areas. Across the Sandhills, conditions remained largely unchanged for the month. Across portions of Boyd and Holt Counties, drought conditions actually deteriorated by the end of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions persisted across all of Garfield County through the end of June. The cooperative observer at Ericson 8WNW reported 3.22 inches of precipitation in June. This was 0.95 inches below the normal of 4.17 inches. The cooperative observer at Burwell reported 2.88 inches of precipitation in June. This was 0.86 inches below the normal of 3.74 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Adequate precipitation in June across western, far southwestern and portions of north central Nebraska, led to some improvement in drought conditions in these areas. Across the Sandhills, conditions remained largely unchanged for the month. Across portions of Boyd and Holt Counties, drought conditions actually deteriorated by the end of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over far northwestern portions of Brown County, moderate (D1) drought conditions persisted through the end of June. Over the remainder of the county, severe (D2) drought conditions persisted through the end of the month. The cooperative observer at Ainsworth reported 2.46 inches of precipitation for June. This was 1.31 inches below the normal of 3.77 inches. The cooperative observer at Elsmere 9ENE reported 3.13 inches of precipitation for June. This was 1.11 inches below the normal of 4.24 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Adequate precipitation in June across western, far southwestern and portions of north central Nebraska, led to some improvement in drought conditions in these areas. Across the Sandhills, conditions remained largely unchanged for the month. Across portions of Boyd and Holt Counties, drought conditions actually deteriorated by the end of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate drought conditions, over central Keya Paha County, improved to abnormally dry (D0) drought conditions by the end of June. Severe (D2) drought conditions improved to moderate (D1) drought conditions by the end of the month. Abnormally dry (D0) drought conditions remained over the western third of the county through the end of the month.  The cooperative observer at Springview 2NW reported 5.61 inches of precipitation in June.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mesoscale convective system developed over southern Missouri during the evening hours of May 8, 2003. This system and its associated cold pool tracked into the northern part of the Mid-South where the airmass and shear profile supported a few severe storms with large hail.

Slow-moving bands of showers and thunderstorms associated with an upper low located over the Lower Mississippi Valley intensified during the afternoon hours on May 10, 2023, when instability peaked. There were isolated reports of large hail and a few microbursts occurred resulting in damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were knocked down on Highway 59 West in Burlison.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another in a series of AR events brought valley rain, mountain snow, and high winds. Due to the valley rain, some snowmelt occurred leading to localized flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Warm temperatures, rainfall, and snowmelt caused flooding of O'Neill Basin Road 755, as well as Twin Bridges road 715B. These roads were closed. Additionally, there were reports of flooding (standing water) for: All Osino Roads, All Ryndon Roads, Spring Valley Parkway and Spring Valley Court (orange traffic barrels were in place). Coal Mine Canyon Road, Burner Basin Roads (rutted roads and retaining water), Last Chance Road (flowing water over roadway at Buzzard. Contact Road by NDOT Station (washout). Spring Creek Parkway (several areas of pooling water). Dirt roads around Elko County were noted as muddy, rutted, and holding water in various areas. In addition to the above the following roads also had some minor flooding: West Bullion Road, Lowe South Fork Road, Lucky Nugget Road, Lower Lamoille Road, Fort Halleck Road, Old Devils Gate Road, Elburz Road, and Kittridge Canyon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A system brought active weather to parts of Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winter Weather caused a Multi-Vehicle crash on I-80 near MM268 (Emigrant Pass). The Crash initially involved 2 semis. The fuel cell of one of the semis became breached, spilling over 25 gallons of Diesel onto the highway, and into a water catch basin. At least 3 additional accidents occurred after the initial crash which closed the westbound lanes for several hours. Eureka County Sheriffs Office and Nevada State Police had to shut down the eastbound lanes in order to shuttle emergency vehicles. Multiple people were transported to Northeastern Regional Hospital for their injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Multi-Day Warm-Up with temperatures in the 60s, and mid 70s (first 70 degree day of the year) caused melting of mid levels and some mountain level snow. This caused flooding to occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Chimney Dam Road was flooded at the crossing of Adam Slough Creek. Warm Temperatures in the 60s to mid 70s caused snow melt of mid-level slopes and perhaps some, but not all of the high level slopes. Martin Creek nearby went into Major Flood Stage and crested at 7.75 feet at 8PM LT.  Photos were submitted by the EM of Humboldt County shortly after this crest.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Multi-Day Warm-Up with temperatures in the 60s, and mid 70s (first 70 degree day of the year) caused melting of mid levels and some mountain level snow. This caused flooding to occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Chimney Dam Road was flooded for a 2nd day in a row, at the crossing of Adam Slough Creek. Warm Temperatures in the 60s to low 70s caused additional snowmelt. Martin Creek nearby went into Major Flood Stage (7.5 feet) for a second day in a row, cresting at a height of 8.22 feet, at 745PM. The EM of Humboldt County sent photos of the flooded road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low-pressure system which had been slowly moving east off the Rocky Mountains finally progressed into central Nebraska. This left eastern Nebraska in the warm sector as a warm front moved north into the area. The SPC issued an Enhanced Risk for severe weather with a 30% hatched for severe hail. There ended up being 19 confirmed tornadoes (3 EF2, 8 EF1, 4 EF0, 4 EFU). There were numerous hail reports the largest of which was 4.5 inches in Pawnee County. Another 4-inch report was received in Richardson County. Flash flooding was also observed in a few locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This is part 1 of the tornado, Part 2  continues into Burt County. The tornado touched down just south of Highway 275, damaging a home, power poles and numerous trees as it entered the Elkhorn River valley. it caused EF-2 damage to a home just south of the Elkhorn River where a porch was ripped off and large trees damaged. The tornado crossed the Elkhorn River where significant tree damage was noted and several center pivots were flipped over. The tornado became wider and impacted additional farmsteads with EF-2 damage, especially as it approached County Road F up to the Dodge and Burt county line. At these farmsteads, several hog barns, machine sheds, and well-built outbuildings were destroyed. Farm equipment was significantly damaged. Windows were broken out of homes, roofs damaged, porches ripped off, and garage doors sucked out. Several people noted that their ears still hurt a day later due to the pressure drop during the tornado. Numerous livestock were injured or killed. The maximum width of this tornado approached one mile as it moved between County Road F and County Road B. A large cattle feedlot was impacted in extreme northeast Dodge county where very large grain bins and well built barns were destroyed. This tornado exhibited multiple vortex damage patterns at times. The tornado appears to have dissipated just north of County Road F in Burt County before developing a new tornado just to the north. Additionally, a satellite tornado was reported near the end of this tornado's life cycle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Adequate precipitation in June across western, far southwestern and portions of north central Nebraska, led to some improvement in drought conditions in these areas. Across the Sandhills, conditions remained largely unchanged for the month. Across portions of Boyd and Holt Counties, drought conditions actually deteriorated by the end of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe (D2) drought conditions persisted across all of Custer County through the end of June. At the Broken Bow Airport, 3.07 inches of precipitation was reported for June. This was 0.45 inches below the normal of 3.52 inches. The cooperative observer at Callaway 8WSW reported 2.51 inches of precipitation in June. The cooperative observer at Anselmo 2WSW reported 1.70 inches of precipitation for June. This was 2.04 inches below the normal of 3.74 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful cold front raced across the Mid-South during the morning hours of March 3, 2023. Strong winds ahead of the front caused scattered damage across northeast Mississippi. Storms developed along the cold front producing damaging winds across northeast Mississippi and a weak tornado in Itawamba County, Mississippi. Behind the departing cold front, a very tight pressure gradient developed resulting in high winds across the Mid-South through the afternoon hours on March 3rd. Winds gusted to over 60 mph at times producing damage across the Mid-South.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds gusted to over 58 mph at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of freezing fog and low clouds moved south from Saskatchewan into northeastern Montana and remained over the area for a couple days.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple episodes of intermittent dense fog with visibility of a quarter mile or less occurred at the Malta Airport AWOS (KM75). The first episode lasted for 7 hours from the night of the 10th to the early morning of the 11th. The second episode lasted 2 1/2 hours on the morning of the 11th.  The third episode lasted 11 hours from the early nighttime hours of the 11th to the morning of the 12th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over far northwestern portions of Holt County, severe (D2) drought conditions improved to moderate (D1) drought conditions by the end of June. Over far northeastern portions of the county, severe (D2) drought conditions deteriorated to extreme (D3) drought conditions by the end of the month. Over the remainder of Holt County, severe (D2) drought persisted through the end of the month. The cooperative observer at O'Neill reported 3.08 inches of rainfall for June. This was 0.40 inches below the normal of 3.48 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Ophelia tracked northward across east central North Carolina and up through central Virginia from early Saturday morning, September 23rd into early Sunday morning, September 24th. The combination of high pressure to the north and the storm resulted in very strong northeast, east and then southeast winds which caused moderate (tidal) coastal flooding across portions of Virginia Beach.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Ophelia tracked northward across east central North Carolina and up through central Virginia from early Saturday morning, September 23rd into early Sunday morning, September 24th. The combination of high pressure to the north and the storm resulted in very strong northeast, east and then southeast winds which caused moderate to major (tidal) coastal flooding over portions of Virginia Beach. Chesapeake Bay Bridge Tunnel reached 5.77 feet MLLW at 218 am on Saturday, September 23. Lynnhaven Inlet reached 5.57 feet MLLW at 236 am on Saturday, September 23.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled front remains situated just to the northwest this morning with a light onshore flow near the surface while persistent southwesterly flow continues aloft. Cooler than normal mid-level temperatures created deeper instability that strengthened diurnally driven sea breeze storms as they develop along the east-coast sea breeze in the afternoon. Deeper moisture was across NE FL and portions of SE GA (generally south and east of Waycross) created more widespread storm coverage, especially along and west of the St Johns River basin as the sea breeze interacted with the river breeze. ||Strong to marginally severe wind gusts of 40-60 mph occurred. Marginal deep layer shear was around 20 kts which create a lower end hail threat. Locally heavy rainfall occurred that created mainly nuisance minor flood issues.

A strong spring storm system moved through the area with ample instability and shear.  Numerous reports of severe weather were received across the tri-state area, including four tornadoes, two in southeast Alabama and two in southwest Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief tornado developed and caused damage at the Enterprise Country Club just north of Enterprise, Alabama. The tornado touched down near the clubhouse, damaging the roof and porch overhang. Debris from the roof was scattered downwind across the golf course. Tree damage was noted along the track as well. The tornado appears to have dissipated before exiting the golf course property. The damage was consistent with an EF0 tornado with winds of 80 to 85 mph. Thanks to Coffee County EMA for assisting with data gathering for this survey.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong portion of the jetstream associated with a deep upper level low brought damaging winds to portions of northern and central NM February 22, 2023. Peak gusts regularly topped 70 mph, with the Santa Fe Airport recording a peak gust of 85 mph. The Magdalena Observatory also measured a peak gust of 93 mph in the San Mateo Mountains of western Socorro County. There were numerous reports of down trees, mostly within the Rio Grande Valley stretching from near Socorro to the Albuquerque metro. The most extreme of these wind damage reports included down transmission or communication towers at the Sandia Crest. This storm system also brought winter storm conditions, mostly to western and northern NM. These include reports of heavy snow, road closures along Interstate 40, and an avalanche at the Taos Ski Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Roswell Industrial Airport ASOS measured a high sustained wind speed of 49 mph.

As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power line was blown down near Route 36 southwest of the Decatur Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper disturbance advanced quickly from California to over southeastern Colorado, causing an area of low pressure to developing in southwestern Kansas. With strong winds aloft associated with the upper disturbance and the quickly developing low pressure present, clearing skies allowed for the stronger winds aloft to be brought to the ground. As a result, strong winds occurred in the Panhandles; Amarillo led the way with a 67 mph gust measured at the airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 1242CST and 1511 CST the mesonet station located near Goodnight measured sustained winds between 40 and 47 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Coastal hazard potential increased through the week as high astronomical spring tides coincided with a persistent onshore flow pattern. Coastal hazards include increasingly strong and frequent rip currents, beach erosion and minor to moderate tidal flooding along the coast, within the Intracoastal Waterway and St. Johns River basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At 8:15 pm on 9/27, the USGS gage BRNG1 at the Village Pier on St. Simons Island measured a peak water level of 2.49 ft MHHW datum. Moderate flooding begins at this gage at 2.5 ft MHHW. On 9/28 at 8:45 pm, the gage measured a peak water level of 2.4 ft MHHW datum. At 10:00 am on 9/30, the gage reached 2.4 ft MHHW. Minor tidal flooding begins at 2 ft at this location.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system and cold front brought light to moderate snowfall across portions of central Missouri, with light snow as far south as the Highway 60 corridor. A band of precipitation with some convective elements moved into portions of central and west central Missouri during the early morning hours of January 12th. Some of the convective elements briefly had sleet with them throughout the morning hours, with precipitation changing over to all snow within about 30 minutes to 2 hours after precipitation onset. Some thunder occurred with the snow in the Lake of the Ozarks region during the early morning hours. As a result, the highest snowfall amounts and rates occurred over central Missouri, with the snow band weakening as it dove southeast across the area during the morning. Precipitation came to an end as flurries and light rain over south central Missouri by early afternoon on January 12th. ||Snowfall amounts generally ranged from 3 to 5 inches across central Missouri and the Lake Ozarks region to as little as 0.5 inches along and just south of the Interstate 44 and Highway 60 corridors across southwestern Missouri. Roads north of Interstate 44, and especially towards the Highway 54 corridor and across the Lake of the Ozarks region, became mostly to completely snow covered during the morning, with partly covered roadways farther south into the Springfield metropolitan area during the morning rush hour into late morning. Multiple slide offs and accidents were reported. About one dozen schools closed for the day, all of which were located across central Missouri.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A band of convective showers had some non-impactful sleet briefly mix in before changing over to light snow during the morning hours of January 12th. Roads remained mostly clear, but were slick at times due to slushy accumulations during higher snowfall rates. A tractor trailer overturned in the county, but injury reports were unknown with this incident. The Cooperative Observer 3 miles north northeast of Northview reported a total snow accumulation of 1.0 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper disturbance advanced quickly from California to over southeastern Colorado, causing an area of low pressure to developing in southwestern Kansas. With strong winds aloft associated with the upper disturbance and the quickly developing low pressure present, clearing skies allowed for the stronger winds aloft to be brought to the ground. As a result, strong winds occurred in the Panhandles; Amarillo led the way with a 67 mph gust measured at the airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The mesonet located 2 NW of Lake McClellan occasionally measured sustained winds between 40 and 49 mph between 1206CST and 1546CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the mid morning through afternoon of January 30th and was mainly sleet. An estimated light glaze of ice accretions and around quarter inch of sleet occurred in the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th. Two crashes occurred as a result of slick conditions. The first was on January 29th when a vehicle on Highway 60 two miles west of Aurora slid on the icy road, crossed the center line, and struck another vehicle. The second was on Highway 97 during the morning of January 30th, when a vehicle slid on the icy road, crossed the center line, and struck another vehicle head on.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak area of low pressure lifted through the Ohio Valley and brought a swath of accumulating snow across Ohio on January 22, 2023. A narrow band of heavier snow, with accumulation rates briefly reaching 1 to 2 per hour, along the I-71 corridor from central Ohio into northern Ohio during the morning and early afternoon. Totals exceeded 6 in this narrow heavier band of snow. The heavy snow rates led to a period of reduced visibility to one-quarter of a mile and snow-covered roads, leading to poor travel conditions. A trained spotter in Lodi measured 7.6 of snow with this storm. Other select spotter reports include 7.2 in Hinckley, 7 in Mansfield, 6.9 in Brunswick, and 6.5 in Hayesville. CoCoRaHS observers also measured 6.5 in Lexington and 6 in Medina.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weak area of low pressure lifted through the Ohio Valley and brought a swath of accumulating snow across the area on January 22, 2023. This was a relatively short-lived burst of heavy snow, with moderate to heavy snow largely confined to a four-hour window between 9 AM and 1 PM when rates of 1 to 2 per hour were reported. With these heavier snow rates, visibility reductions to one-quarter of a mile and snow-covered roads occurred. A trained spotter measured 7 of snow in Mansfield with this storm, the highest total in the county. A CoCoRaHS observer measured 6.5 of snow in Lexington. Observers at Mansfield-Lahm airport measured 5.4 of snow with this storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A silo was blown over just outside of Decatur.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree limb was blown down on Highlawn Road in Decatur.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An atmospheric river brought an abundance of moisture to Eastern Utah. This, paired with the passage of an upper level trough across the Northern Rockies and associated cold front, resulted in moderate to heavy snow for the northern and southern mountains. Mild air associated with the atmospheric river kept snow levels high with mostly all rain or a rain/snow mix in the valleys. Winds gusted up to 58 mph at times in the mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Generally 5 to 9 inches of snow fell across the area with locally higher amounts of up to 16 inches estimated at the Mosby Mountain SNOTEL site. Much of the snow fell in 12 hours or less. Winds gusted up to 58 mph at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper disturbance advanced quickly from California to over southeastern Colorado, causing an area of low pressure to developing in southwestern Kansas. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent storm system lifted northeast from Oklahoma through Arkansas and Missouri on January 24th and 25th, bringing widespread precipitation across the Missouri Ozarks beginning as rain during the late morning and afternoon on January 24th before changing over to snow during the afternoon and evening. This snow continued into the morning hours of January 25th before coming to an end as the storm system exited the region.||Snowfall amounts generally ranged from 1 to 3 inches for areas along and northwest of a Joplin to Stockton to Lake of the Ozarks line. There was a sharp cutoff in heavy snow near Interstate 44, with many locations seeing 6 to 8 inches south of Interstate 44 and up to 12 inches near West Plains. Roads became completely covered and slick across the region for the evening commute of January 24th and also into the morning commute on January 25th due to the ongoing snow. Several slide offs and vehicle accidents occurred as a result of the slick road conditions. Numerous schools were closed across the region on January 25th, with some even doing early dismissals on January 24th. Some schools also remain closed into January 26th in the areas that received higher snow amounts across south central Missouri. Total power outages reached over 50 thousand across southern and south central Missouri from the heavy snow, with numerous power outages continuing in Howell, Shannon and Oregon Counties into January 27th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Precipitation started as rain during the afternoon of January 24th before changing over to snow during the late afternoon, with the snow then continuing into the morning of January 25th. Snow amounts between 2 and 2.5 inches fell across the county. A CoCoRaHS report of a measured storm total of 2.5 inches of snow was received from 6.3 miles ESE of Nevada, with a measured 2.0 inches at the COOP site in Nevada. Roads became snow covered and slippery, with a one vehicle injury accident occurring on Highway B east of Sheldon as the vehicle slid off the road, struck an embankment and overturned. Some schools were closed on January 25th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful cold front raced across the Mid-South during the morning hours of March 3, 2023. Strong winds ahead of the front caused scattered damage across northeast Mississippi. Storms developed along the cold front producing damaging winds across northeast Mississippi and a weak tornado in Itawamba County, Mississippi. Behind the departing cold front, a very tight pressure gradient developed resulting in high winds across the Mid-South through the afternoon hours on March 3rd. Winds gusted to over 60 mph at times producing damage across the Mid-South.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds gusted over 58 mph at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Ophelia tracked northward across east central North Carolina and up through central Virginia from early Saturday morning, September 23rd into early Sunday morning, September 24th. The combination of high pressure to the north and the storm resulted in very strong northeast, east and then southeast winds which caused moderate to major (tidal) coastal flooding across portions of the James River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tropical Storm Ophelia tracked northward across east central North Carolina and up through central Virginia from early Saturday morning, September 23rd into early Sunday morning, September 24th. The combination of high pressure to the north and the storm resulted in very strong northeast, east and then southeast winds which caused moderate to major (tidal) coastal flooding over portions of James City county. Jamestown reached 5.23 feet MLLW at 542 am on Saturday, September 23.

CZ_NAME: UPPER SANTA CRUZ RIVER AND ALTAR VALLEYS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure aloft strengthened over Arizona and created a period of very hot temperatures August 25-30 across southeast Arizona. High temperatures were 6 to 14 degrees above normal causing the Moderate to Major Heat Risk categories to be reached and numerous high temperature records to be established. A total of eleven heat-related fatalities were reported by the Pima County Medical Examiner.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures of 7 to 14 degrees above normal caused the Major Heat Risk category to be reached across southeast Pima County, south central Pinal County and the lower elevations of Santa Cruz County August 27-29. Record highs included 111 degrees at Picacho Peak; 108 at Sasabe; and 104 at the Nogales Airport, all on August 29.  While not a record, Picacho Peak reached 112 degrees on the 28th. The Pima County Medical Examiner determined that heat was the primary cause of death for two individuals found in the desert of southeast Pima County (one on the 28th about 8 miles southwest of Three Points and one on the 29th just east of the Baboquivari Mountains at 3800 ft near Elkhorn Ranch).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system brought a prolonged 24 to 30 hour period of freezing drizzle across the area, beginning during the early overnight hours of January 29th and continuing throughout the day on January 29th before ending in the early morning hours of January 30th. An additional wintry mix of mainly heavy sleet as well as light snow and light freezing rain impacted areas mainly along and south of the Interstate 44 corridor, starting in the mid to late morning and ending from west to east across the area during the afternoon into early evening. ||Ice accretions were a widespread glaze, with ASOS measured flat ice accumulations ranging from 0.05 inches in West Plains to a max of 0.33 inches in Springfield. Sleet and snow accumulations, which were mainly in the form of sleet, ranged from around 0.25 inches in locations near Interstate 44 to between 1.0 to 1.5 inches near the southern Missouri border.||There were numerous crashes and slide offs across the area on January 29th and 30th, with the Missouri Department of Transportation showing covered and slick roadways throughout the event. One of the crashes in Morgan County also resulted in a fatality. Some roads south of Interstate 44 even remained covered into the day on January 31st. Numerous schools and businesses across the area were closed on January 30th due to the winter road impacts, with numerous schools remaining closed on January 31st along and south of Interstate 44 where roads remained covered and slick.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two rounds of wintry precipitation fell across the county. The first round began during the very early morning hours of January 29th as freezing drizzle and lingered into the early morning of January 30th. The second round fell during the morning through afternoon of January 30th and was mainly sleet, but mixed with some snow pellets and flurries. A CoCoRaHS report in Shoal Creek Estate measured 0.5 inches of sleet accumulation. There was also an estimated glaze of ice across the county. Roads became covered and slick with numerous schools closed on January 30th and January 31st. A crash on Highway 60 eastbound also closed both lanes of traffic, but details on number of vehicles and any injuries is unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracking northwest of Maine drew a warm front across the region during the 6th. Overrunning precipitation developed above trapped low level cold air during the afternoon of the 5th. Precipitation across northern Maine was a wintry mix of snow...sleet and freezing rain. The wintry mix persisted into the morning of the 6th. Warning criteria sleet accumulations occurred during the early morning hours of the 6th. Sleet accumulations across northern areas ranged from around 0.50 inch up to 2.0 inches...along with generally a tenth to quarter inch of freezing rain and 1 to 3 inches of snow.  Across Downeast areas...ice accumulations generally ranged from a tenth to a quarter of an inch though isolated totals up to a half inch were reported across portions of Washington county. Sleet accumulations were generally 0.50 inch or less.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total sleet accumulations were up to 2 inches. Snow accumulations were generally less than an inch...along with a tenth to quarter inch of ice.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure aloft strengthened over Arizona and created a period of very hot temperatures August 25-30 across southeast Arizona. High temperatures were 6 to 14 degrees above normal causing the Moderate to Major Heat Risk categories to be reached and numerous high temperature records to be established. A total of eleven heat-related fatalities were reported by the Pima County Medical Examiner.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures of 7 to 11 degrees above normal caused the Major Heat Risk category to be reached across eastern Pima County August 27-30. Record highs at Tucson International Airport included 109 degrees on August 28 and 108 on the 29th. The Pima County Medical Examiner determined that heat was the primary cause of death for one individual found indoors on the 28th with a nonfunctioning AC unit in Green Valley where the temperature topped out at 103 degrees. Heat was found to be a contributing factor in the death of four individuals outdoors in Tucson during the period. Two were found outdoors and also experienced a complicating factor of drug toxicity. Three had complicating factors of drug toxicity and one suffered from other health conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Multi-Day Warm-Up with temperatures in the 60s, and mid 70s (first 70 degree day of the year) caused melting of mid levels and some mountain level snow. This caused flooding to occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: SR 278 was closed from Carlin to US-50 (88 Mile Stretch). At MM73, Water was reported over the roadway, which caused the highway to collapse (sinkhole). Other areas of flooding were observed, where 12 plus inches of water was reported over the southbound side of the highway. The road remains closed indefinitely.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Even though an old outflow boundary was across southeast Missouri and the far southern portions of Illinois during the morning hours, the boundary dissipated, allowing 75+ dew points to surge north along the Mississippi River. As skies cleared the atmosphere was able to quickly destabilize. Surface based CAPEs were in excess of 3000 J/kg with 40kts of 0 to 6km bulk shear. This combined with a shortwave trough that moved eastward across the region, produced strong to severe storms. There were numerous reports of damaging winds and some reports of large hail. There were three fatalities due to fallen trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread wind damage across the northern portions of the city as a line of storms moved through. Numerous large trees, tree limbs, power poles and power lines were blown down. A woman who was waiting for the storm to pass was killed when a large tree was blown over, crushing the car in the alley of the 4100 block of Chouteau Avenue. Two historical cemeteries, Calvary and Bellefontaine, sustained widespread damage. Around 100 trees at Calvary and nearly 40 significant trees and 100 smaller ones at Bellefontaine, were either uprooted or snapped off near the base, as well as numerous tree limbs. Several gravestones were either damaged or destroyed by fallen trees and/or tree limbs. A large tree was uprooted in the 3000 block of Longfellow Boulevard, landing on a house causing major roof damage. A couple of power poles were snapped off along Hall Street. Over 100,000 customers (St. Louis County/St. Louis City) were without power due to this storm. It took a little over 4 days to restore power to all of them.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure aloft strengthened over Arizona and created a period of very hot temperatures August 25-30 across southeast Arizona. High temperatures were 6 to 14 degrees above normal causing the Moderate to Major Heat Risk categories to be reached and numerous high temperature records to be established. A total of eleven heat-related fatalities were reported by the Pima County Medical Examiner.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very hot temperatures of 7 to 14 degrees above normal caused the Major Heat Risk category to be reached across southeast Pima County, south central Pinal County and the lower elevations of Santa Cruz County August 27-29. Record highs included 111 degrees at Picacho Peak; 108 at Sasabe; and 104 at the Nogales Airport, all on August 29.  While not a record, Picacho Peak reached 112 degrees on the 28th. The Pima County Medical Examiner determined that heat was the primary cause of death for two individuals found in the desert of southeast Pima County (one on the 28th about 8 miles southwest of Three Points and one on the 29th just east of the Baboquivari Mountains at 3800 ft near Elkhorn Ranch).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent storm system lifted northeast from Oklahoma through Arkansas and Missouri on January 24th and 25th, bringing widespread precipitation across the Missouri Ozarks beginning as rain during the late morning and afternoon on January 24th before changing over to snow during the afternoon and evening. This snow continued into the morning hours of January 25th before coming to an end as the storm system exited the region.||Snowfall amounts generally ranged from 1 to 3 inches for areas along and northwest of a Joplin to Stockton to Lake of the Ozarks line. There was a sharp cutoff in heavy snow near Interstate 44, with many locations seeing 6 to 8 inches south of Interstate 44 and up to 12 inches near West Plains. Roads became completely covered and slick across the region for the evening commute of January 24th and also into the morning commute on January 25th due to the ongoing snow. Several slide offs and vehicle accidents occurred as a result of the slick road conditions. Numerous schools were closed across the region on January 25th, with some even doing early dismissals on January 24th. Some schools also remain closed into January 26th in the areas that received higher snow amounts across south central Missouri. Total power outages reached over 50 thousand across southern and south central Missouri from the heavy snow, with numerous power outages continuing in Howell, Shannon and Oregon Counties into January 27th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Precipitation started as rain during the afternoon of January 24th before changing over to snow during the late afternoon, with the snow then continuing into the morning of January 25th. Widespread snow amounts between 5 and 8 inches fell across the county. A public report of a measured storm total of 8.0 inches of snow was received from 2 miles WNW of Norwood, with a measured 7.0 inches in Mansfield, and 6.5 inches in Hartville. Roads became snow covered and slippery. Around 1500 power outages also occurred across the county due to the heavy snow. Some schools had early release on January 24th, with numerous schools closed on January 25th and January 26th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Adequate precipitation in June across western, far southwestern and portions of north central Nebraska, led to some improvement in drought conditions in these areas. Across the Sandhills, conditions remained largely unchanged for the month. Across portions of Boyd and Holt Counties, drought conditions actually deteriorated by the end of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over far northeastern portions of Lincoln County, severe (D2) drought conditions persisted through the end of the June. The cooperative observer at Wallace 2W reported 1.83 inches of precipitation in June. This was 2.00 inches below the normal of 3.83 inches. The cooperative observer at Hershey 5SSE reported 1.82 inches of precipitation for the month. This was 2.00 inches below the normal of 3.82 inches. At the North Platte Airport, 2.59 inches of precipitation fell in June. This was 0.95 inches below the normal of 3.54 inches. The cooperative observer at Brady reported 2.32 inches of precipitation for June.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper disturbance advanced quickly from California to over southeastern Colorado, causing an area of low pressure to developing in southwestern Kansas. With strong winds aloft associated with the upper disturbance and the quickly developing low pressure present, clearing skies allowed for the stronger winds aloft to be brought to the ground. As a result, strong winds occurred in the Panhandles; Amarillo led the way with a 67 mph gust measured at the airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The mesonet located 10 ESE of Valley de Oro occasionally measured sustained winds between 40 and 49 mph between 1203CST and 1429CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Powerlines were blown down on the 1300 block of West Enos Avenue in Springfield.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracking northwest of Maine drew a warm front across the region during the 6th. Overrunning precipitation developed above trapped low level cold air during the afternoon of the 5th. Precipitation across northern Maine was a wintry mix of snow...sleet and freezing rain. The wintry mix persisted into the morning of the 6th. Warning criteria sleet accumulations occurred during the early morning hours of the 6th. Sleet accumulations across northern areas ranged from around 0.50 inch up to 2.0 inches...along with generally a tenth to quarter inch of freezing rain and 1 to 3 inches of snow.  Across Downeast areas...ice accumulations generally ranged from a tenth to a quarter of an inch though isolated totals up to a half inch were reported across portions of Washington county. Sleet accumulations were generally 0.50 inch or less.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total sleet accumulations were up to around an inch. Snow accumulations ranged from 2 to 4 inches...along with a tenth to quarter inch of ice.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful cold front raced across the Mid-South during the morning hours of March 3, 2023. Strong winds ahead of the front caused scattered damage across northeast Mississippi. Storms developed along the cold front producing damaging winds across northeast Mississippi and a weak tornado in Itawamba County, Mississippi. Behind the departing cold front, a very tight pressure gradient developed resulting in high winds across the Mid-South through the afternoon hours on March 3rd. Winds gusted to over 60 mph at times producing damage across the Mid-South.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds gusted over 58 mph at times.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Farmington, there were cars stuck in street flooding at the Rt 9 exit ramp to I-84.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Even though an old outflow boundary was across southeast Missouri and the far southern portions of Illinois during the morning hours, the boundary dissipated, allowing 75+ dew points to surge north along the Mississippi River. As skies cleared the atmosphere was able to quickly destabilize. Surface based CAPEs were in excess of 3000 J/kg with 40kts of 0 to 6km bulk shear. This combined with a shortwave trough that moved eastward across the region, produced strong to severe storms. There were numerous reports of damaging winds and some reports of large hail. There were three fatalities due to fallen trees.

Strong upper level ridge built up over the region from July 25th through 29th. This ushered in much warmer air and higher dewpoints. So heat index values 100+ were reported from July 25th through 29th. The hottest days were July 27th, 28th and 29th, so an excessive heat warning was issued for portions of northeast/east central Missouri and west central/southwest Illinois. At least 50 people were seen in hospital emergency room departments during this three day period in St. Louis County/City for heat-related illnesses.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Excessive heat across the county with highs in the mid to upper 90s each day. Heat index values as high as 110 both days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was across portions of southeast Missouri. With plenty of instability, moisture and lift near the boundary, several strong to severe storms developed in this area. There were several reports of damaging winds and large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Widespread hail damage was reported in Ellington due to hail up to golf ball size. Several windshields on vehicles were broken, as well as windows on several homes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Warming temperatures into the 60s and 70s caused rock slides to occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moisture locked up in mountain snow began to melt in Lamoille Canyon from temperatures in the 60s and 70s. This caused large rocks and boulders to fall onto and close USFS-660 from the Powerhouse Group Picnic Area to Thomas Canyon Campground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowmelt from warming temperatures in the 60s caused minor flooding to occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An area of minor flooding occurred and water was observed over SR-226 at MM15 with small rocks spotted along the road as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Upper-Level Jet coinciding along the leading edge of a ridge of high pressure, caused breezy conditions across NE Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station PEQNV I-80 Pequop Summit, Elevation 6954 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Upper-Level Jet coinciding along the leading edge of a ridge of high pressure, caused breezy conditions across NE Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station PQRNV I-80 Pequop Summit, Elevation 6954 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Broad northwest flow aloft brought repeated rounds of showers and thunderstorms to Arkansas. A stagnant weather pattern promoted water levels to rise above flood state across portion of Arkansas. Less rainfall was noted later in the month, thus all rivers fell below flood stage before May ended.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall brought minor flooding to the Little Missouri River at Boughton in mid-May.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak area of low pressure tracked west to east along a stationary boundary, south of New England during the overnight of February 22nd into February 23rd. The storm was a quick mover with about 6-8 hours of snowfall that accumulated 3 to 8 inches across the region, the heaviest in the southern and central Green Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A general 4 to 7 inches of snow fell across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front near the area forced torrential thunderstorms in a tropical airmass resulting in widespread flash flooding in NY. The first round of thunderstorms occurred early in the morning on July 16th. Another round of thunderstorms occurred later in the afternoon. The tropical airmass had CAPE values 1500 - 2000 J/kg with PWATs 2.2-2.4 inches. The torrential thunderstorms produced rainfall rates as much as 3 inches an hour. Rainfall amounts totaled a widespread 2-4 inches across Long Island with localized spots seeing as much as 5 inches of rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding on Southern State Parkway westbound at Exit 44W with all lanes closed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary remained over the area which produced multiple rounds of torrential rainfall form heavy thunderstorms from July 9th through July 10th. CAPE values of 2500 to 3500 J/kg and PWAT values of near 1.8 allowed heavy thunderstorm development to produce rainfall rates of 2-3 inches per hour at times. There were parts of the area that receive anywhere from 3-5 inches of rain in a several hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three cars submerged near Bank Street and Broad Street due to flooding.

There were many streets closed, many cars stranded in flood waters, and several houses with flooded basements or first floors.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Pawtucket, cars were stuck in flood waters near Armisticle Blvd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak upper-level wave moving through southwest flow aloft, acting on an environment with 1000 to 1500 J/kg of MUCAPE in the vicinity of a surface trough, resulted in scattered thunderstorms across far southeast South Dakota, far northeast Nebraska, northwest Iowa, and southwest Minnesota during the evening of April 19th. The strongest storms produced severe hail ranging from 1.0 to 1.5 inches in diameter.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail 0.88 inch in diameter fell 1 mile south-southeast of Ponca.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Bolton, 5-6 trees were snapped in a straight line along Rt 117/Main St.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wind gradient around a large upper level circulation resulted in widespread winds of 30 to 40 mph and gusts from 45 to 65 mph east of the James River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusted as high as 49 mph at a personal weather station in Terril, and 48 mph 3 miles south of Lake Park and 7 miles southwest of Milford.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved up from the North Pacific past Kodiak Island and into the Kenai Peninsula on 2/5, with very strong winds over the Gulf spreading into parts of Bristol Bay and the Kenai Peninsula.  These winds combined with light snow to produce areas of blowing snow and visibility reduced down to less than a mile for several hours in a few spots, including Portage Valley, King Salmon and New Stuyahok.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Portage AWOS recorded strong easterly winds gusting to around 45 MPH with light to moderate snow and blowing snow, with visibility reduced to 1/2 mile or less between about 10 AM and 5 PM AKST 2/5.  The Chugach National Forest Avalanche Center also reported 1/2 mile visibility or less at times with 6 inches of new snowfall and wind gusting between 25 and 35 mph at 2 PM AKST the same day.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches occurred across the area. A lot of accidents occurred on Interstate 90.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary remained over the area which produced multiple rounds of torrential rainfall form heavy thunderstorms from July 9th through July 10th. CAPE values of 2500 to 3500 J/kg and PWAT values of near 1.8 allowed heavy thunderstorm development to produce rainfall rates of 2-3 inches per hour at times. There were parts of the area that receive anywhere from 3-5 inches of rain in a several hour period with some spots seeing upwards of 8 inches. This allowed for the issuance of a localized Flash Flood Emergency for portion of the Lower Hudson Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NY 293 is closed due to flooding in both directions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Even though an old outflow boundary was across southeast Missouri and the far southern portions of Illinois during the morning hours, the boundary dissipated, allowing 75+ dew points to surge north along the Mississippi River. As skies cleared the atmosphere was able to quickly destabilize. Surface based CAPEs were in excess of 3000 J/kg with 40kts of 0 to 6km bulk shear. This combined with a shortwave trough that moved eastward across the region, produced strong to severe storms. There were numerous reports of damaging winds and some reports of large hail. There were three fatalities due to fallen trees.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak area of low pressure tracked west to east along a stationary boundary, south of New England during the overnight of February 22nd into February 23rd. The storm was a quick mover with about 6-8 hours of snowfall that accumulated 3 to 8 inches across the region, the heaviest in the southern and central Green Mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A general 4 to 7 inches of snow fell across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dangerously hot conditions plagued just about all of North and Central Texas in mid July, with heat indices at or above 110 along with ambient temperatures at or above 105.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Excessive heat returned to the region with temperatures at or above 105 along with heat indices at or above 110.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough breaking down a ridge brought strong zonal flow to the region. Weak ridgetop stability resulted in strong winds along the immediate eastern slopes and out to the Cut Bank area for a brief period Sunday the 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station DELMT Dellwo measured two gusts in excess of 58 mph, including a peak gust of 61 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a vigorous upper-level wave tracked eastward out of the southern Rockies, surface low pressure formed over Texas then lifted northeastward into the Ohio River Valley on March 3rd.  Analysis from the evening of March 2nd showed a 991mb low over central Texas...with the low rapidly deepening to 976mb as it tracked into southern Indiana by the afternoon of March 3rd.  Surface pressures of these magnitudes are rare across the Midwest and are in fact more comparable to a tropical storm or hurricane.  To the north of the low track, central Illinois got battered with very strong gradient winds.  Northeasterly gusts frequently topped 50 mph...with the highest gusts in excess of 60 mph focused in a corridor from Decatur and Mattoon northeastward to Champaign.  The highest gust recorded was 72 mph at the Mattoon Airport.  Given the high wind gusts from an unusual direction (northeast), several trees, tree branches, and power lines were downed across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree was blown across East Elwin Road just west of Mount Zion.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deamplifying mid level shortwave with dewpoints in the 70s and decent instability brought scattered thunderstorms and widespread flash flooding to Rhode Island and Massachusetts. There were many streets closed, many cars stranded in flood waters, and several houses with flooded basements or first floors.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Cumberland, water entered homes on Fairhaven Rd. Marshall Ave was flooded and water came into a home through the basement window on Mowry Ave.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wind gradient around a large upper level circulation resulted in widespread winds of 30 to 40 mph and gusts from 45 to 65 mph east of the James River.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusted as high as 45 mph at the Automated Weather Observing System site KLRJ in Le Mars.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong non-thunderstorm winds across portions of northwest Iowa produced isolated damage during the early morning hours of April 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mesonet station FW1255 6 miles west-northwest of Fostoria measured a wind gust to 57 mph and mesonet station FW7399 2 miles west-southwest of Terril measured a wind gust to 55 mph. The county emergency manager reported a roof peeled off a mobile home in Spirit Lake, shingle damage in Superior, and damage to a hay shed and shingles 4 miles east-southeast of Orleans.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal system brought a period of heavy rain, flash flooding, and embedded thunderstorms to southern New England from the morning to mid evening. In addition to much tree damage from straight line winds, there was one tornado in Connecticut, 2 in Rhode Island, and 1 in Massachusetts. These all occurred in the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: In Chaplin, a tree and wires were down and a utility pole was snapped.
